him the blood of Tunare's faithful will mingle with the blood of Tunare's children. Though healing his birthright be, destruction will be in his touch and Death twice shall he bring. Through his powers shall his firstborn be joined with the mother. On this day death will become life forever.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uraffphoenixheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raff Phoenixheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#CC9900>(3/5/01 4:51:13 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mayt - The Power Within</span><hr size=1> The Power Within 1<br>
<br>
&quot;Hi mommy! We're home!&quot; Maella shouted as she entered the tavern. She ignored the few patrons sitting around the room and ran straight to the kitchen at the back of the building. Mayt smiled. It didn't seem to matter what his daughter did, it always brought a smile to his face. He followed Maella to the kitchen, slowly working his way through the tables. He paused as he reached the table where an older Wood Elf sat, sipping at his drink by himself.<br>
<br>
&quot;Greetings Jorgatha. It is nice to see you again.&quot; He smiled and nodded at the older Wood Elf. &quot;How has your son been? I had heard he was not feeling well.&quot;<br>
<br>
Jorgatha finished a long pull at the mug in his hand and set it down on the table, his hands cradling it. He looked intently at this drink for a moment, as if he was steeling himself to speak. Finally he looked up at Mayt, his green eyes filled with sadness. &quot;The Mother has called him to her side, Mayt. He no longer walks the Faydark.&quot; His voice was thick with emotion and he couldn’t hold his gaze on Mayt for long before returning his eyes to the mug he was rotating slowly with his hands.<br>
<br>
Mayt's face fell but he struggled to keep his emotions in check. &quot;I am extremely sorry to hear that, friend.” He said quietly. “The last I had heard it looked as though he would recover from his ordeal at the hands of the Orcs. I cannot effectively convey my sorrow. I truly am sorry.&quot; He put his hand on Jorgatha's shoulder in an effort to comfort him. The older Elf responded by putting his hand on top of Mayt's.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you for your kind words Mayt.” He said, turning his head to look at him again. “I take some comfort in knowing he's with Tunare now, and finally at peace.”<br>
<br>
Mayt nodded again and squeezed his friend's shoulder. A shudder ran through him as he briefly contemplated the possibility of losing Maella. She was an enormous part of his life now, and the mere thought of her death nearly brought tears to his eyes. The world is too cruel a place, he thought.<br>
<br>
&quot;If there might be something Ianarae or myself can do, please do not hesitate to ask. We know what it is like to have a child, and thank Erollisi and Tunare every day for her safety. We feel your pain in our hearts.&quot;<br>
<br>
Jorgatha smiled, his lips tight, and simply nodded. Mayt squeezed his shoulder again and continued to the kitchen.<br>
<br>
Inside the kitchen he found his beautiful wife, Ianarae, and his father Tyle. He moved behind Ianarae, who was busy with dishes, and hugged her warmly. She kept her hands in the sink but turned her head toward him and kissed him lightly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Maella tells me she had a good time today with her Daddy,&quot; she said as Mayt reached for a drying towel.<br>
<br>
Mayt smiled. “Yes, I think we did. The fay drakes are most likely relieved to be rid of us so they can have some peace.” He glanced at his father across the room, standing in front of the stove. &quot;She tells me that her grandfather has offered to make her anything she wishes.&quot;<br>
<br>
Maella was sitting on the counter beside the sink, swinging her legs against the cupboard below. &quot;Yup, and I want pick cold gator and bat crunches&quot; she said happily.<br>
<br>
Ianarae looked at Mayt and then at Tyle who was busy mixing a stew in a large pot on the stove.<br>
<br>
&quot;Father,” she began, “you must stop spoiling her like this. Soon she won't eat anything but batwing crunchies and pickled gator.&quot; Ianarae's voice was light and teasing.<br>
<br>
Tyle stopped stirring long enough to pull the large wooden spoon out of the stew and place it to his lips. He turned to look at Ianarae while he sipped at its contents.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's my job to spoil her,&quot; he said hoarsely, his voice barely a whisper. &quot;I'm her grandfather, after all. If I don't spoil her, who will?&quot; He paused, considering his creation thoughtfully as he rolled it around his mouth. He frowned, turned toward the stove and reached for a jar of spices above the stove.<br>
<br>
Ianarae sighed and looked at Mayt again, the facade of a frown on her face. &quot;Her father does well enough at spoiling her. Between the two of you, I doubt she will grow up with any manners whatsoever.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, my daughter,&quot; he said, his voice rasping as he stirred the stew, &quot;that is your problem - not mine.&quot; He reached up to his neck and absently rubbed at the ugly scar running across his throat. &quot;Her grandmother isn't here, so I must do the work of two grandparents.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mayt shrugged at Ianarae and grabbed a wet plate from the drying rack. His wife sighed and returned to her washing. As he finished drying the first plate he placed it on the shelf above the sink and then looked over to his father with concern.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your voice sounds a bit weak today Father. Are you feeling alright?&quot;<br>
<br>
Tyle grumbled at the stove inaudibly as a young High Elf entered the kitchen, a tray on her hand. <br>
<br>
She laughed lightly and said &quot;He can't talk today because he spent most of last night drinking with his old friends.&quot; She looked at Tyle with a wry smile. &quot;And the singing didn't help much either, I'd guess.&quot; <br>
<br>
Tyle glanced at her and grumbled again. &quot;Don't I pay you to be waiting on tables?&quot; he asked, sarcasm melding in his raspy voice.<br>
<br>
She placed the tray on the counter at the side and tilted her head at Tyle. &quot;Well, I would, if I had any stew to serve them, but the cook seems to be taking longer than usual perfecting his art today.&quot;<br>
<br>
Tyle grumbled again as the High Elf giggled. Ianarae joined her laughter and said, &quot;I think it’s more than just his stew that’s a bit slow today, Cyrileal. Too much ale makes an old Elf a bit dull-witted.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye,&quot; Cyrileal agreed. &quot;And old Songwhisper was drinking enough ale to keep him singing well into the night.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mayt smiled at his father and the way the two women badgered him. He hadn't seen his father this light hearted in many years, possibly ever. Although he was too young to remember it, he knew very well how drastically his father's life had changed almost one hundred years ago during the orc invasion of Kelethin. His father had been, at that time, a well-known Bard, and he fought bravely defending Kelethin. He paid dearly for the defense that day, however, when an orc's blade nearly took his life. He lived, but the orc's foul weapon all but destroyed his voice. Although he was famous as one of the only High Elves to ever become a songweaver, his career as a Bard ended that day. <br>
<br>
Tyle's injuries went far beyond the physical. His wife, his sister and her husband were killed in that battle. He thought his niece had also died and only found out recently that she had survived. Without his voice, and without a family, Tyle retired from the life he'd loved so much and took over the Torvanni's Venom tavern in Felwithe. Even though his voice had been reduced to a quiet rasp, he continued to sing, especially to the patrons of the Venom, and soon acquired the moniker &quot;Songwhisper&quot;. To this day all his friends and customers called him by the name. His whispering added a plaintive touch to all his songs and gave even the most uplifting lyrics a mournful tone.<br>
<br>
Tyle had been a difficult father, and Mayt often wondered if he could ever earn his respect. Unfortunately, in his grief Tyle became desperate for a son that would carry on the family tradition. Mayt’s mother, Ghaiayna, was an accomplished Cleric, and so was Tyle’s mother, Mayet, whom Mayt was named for. After Ghaiayna’s death, Tyle became obsessed with having a Cleric in the family and pushed Mayt to become a Cleric of Tunare. Unfortunately, Mayt failed spectacularly as a Cleric, and his father brooded on this failure for most of his son’s life. It wasn’t until shortly before Mayt married Ianarae that Tyle finally accepted his son for what he was. The addition of Maella to the family only brightened Tyle’s life more, and Mayt marveled daily at the affect his daughter had on Tyle’s disposition. Smiling to himself, he placed another dry plate on the shelf with the others.<br>
<br>
<br>
Ianarae put the last dish on the drying rack, wiped her hands on a towel and gave Mayt a quick hug.<br>
<br>
&quot;I need to go to the market and get some good food,&quot; she said and then shot a stern look at her father in law. &quot;Our daughter needs to eat more than just batwing crunchies, and our customers will be wanting bread with the newest Songwhisper stew masterpiece.&quot;<br>
<br>
Mayt grabbed the last dish and started drying it. &quot;I shall come with you then, dear. I need to visit my guild for a few moments.&quot; He looked at Maella who had moved over to sit on a stool beside her grandfather. &quot;Can you watch Maella while we are gone father?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;As long as you don't mind me spoiling her,&quot; he croaked sarcastically.<br>
<br>
“And if he’s too busy with his stew, I’ll make sure she’s taken care of,” Cyrileal said as she left the kitchen for the common room.<br>
<br>
Ianarae started to leave but stopped and turned back to her husband. She reached out and pulled the drying towl from where Mayt had left it on his shoulder. “Are you planning on washing dishes at your guild hall as well?” <br>
<br>
Mayt looked surprised to see the towel on his shoulder. “Oh,” he said. “I forgot I was carrying that around with me.” He grinned weakly at his wife.<br>
<br>
Ianarae laughed and led him out of the kitchen, his hand in hers.  <br>
<br>
 <br>
