<br>
It was the way the voice said his name that made Mayt stop in the hallway to listen to the conversation. There was something odd about the voice – something not quite right.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mayt? Yes, of course I know him. He is one of our accomplished students.&quot; Mayt recognized the voice of his teacher Master Tarker.<br>
<br>
&quot;Is he the one who had the difficulty when he was younger?&quot; the voice asked. Something about the way the person behind the voice asked the question made Mayt feel uncomfortable, even vulnerable.<br>
<br>
“Yes, we found out about Mayt when he was a child and, at that time, he was having much difficulty with controlling his magical energies.” Tarker answered. “Why do you ask?”<br>
<br>
&quot;It is very important that I speak to him as soon as possible.&quot; The stranger's voice was calm and measured, yet there was an urgency about his voice.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why would that be?&quot; Tarker asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;It is not something I want to discuss at this time, but it is very important, as I already said.&quot;<br>
<br>
“I have not seen him this day, but his family runs a tavern in Felwithe called Torvanni’s Venom. I am sure you would find him there, or, at the least, find more information regarding his whereabouts.”<br>
<br>
Mayt’s heart skipped a beat.<br>
<br>
“Thank you. You have been most helpful.” Mayt could imagine the owner of the voice was smiling. From the accent he thought he might be from the far west coast of Antonica, maybe even Erudin.<br>
<br>
“Good luck to you then,” Tarker said. <br>
<br>
Mayt heard footsteps from behind a door moving toward the hallway he was in. Something about the situation made him feel uncomfortable so he quickly cast an invisibility spell and moved quietly off to one side of the hall. A moment later a door opened into the corridor and a tall, powerfully built Erudite stepped through. He walked down the hallway toward Mayt, great confidence in his stride. As he passed Mayt, oblivious to the Elf’s presence, he pulled a light hood over his dark hair and shifted his cloak around his body. Within the swirl of fabric Mayt saw the glint of metal on a mighty sword hanging from the man’s belt. From his brief glance, he was impressed by the sheer size of the weapon. The man was tall, for an Erudite, but the sword hung nearly to his calf, and the handle reached high above his waist.<br>
<br>
Mayt stood deathly still as the man walked by but allowed his eyes to follow him as he continued down the hall. His boots made a loud clicking sound as they struck the worn stones that formed the guildhall floor. As soon as the stranger was out of sight and earshot Mayt allowed himself to breathe again, hurried down the hall to the room he’d just seen the man exit from and went in. Dropping his invisibility spell, he greeted his former teacher.<br>
<br>
“Greetings Master Tarker,” Mayt said with a deep bow of respect. “How does the day please you?”<br>
<br>
The teacher looked surprised to see his old student. “Why Mayt! How unusual! I was just talking about you. An Erudite left here not two minutes ago. He was inquiring about you. He would not say what his business was, but he insisted he see you as soon as possible. I sent him to the Venom. If you hurry, you might catch him.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you Master. Do you know this Erudite?” He asked.<br>
<br>
The older Elf shook his head. “No, Mayt, I do not know him. He just left, son. I am sure you could catch him.”<br>
<br>
Mayt bowed. “Thank you teacher. I shall endeavor to catch him then.” He turned to leave, stopped, and turned around to face his old teacher again. “Master?” he asked.<br>
<br>
Tarker tilted his head curiously. “Yes my son?”<br>
<br>
“Did this Erudite seem …” Mayt struggled to find the right words. “Dangerous?”<br>
<br>
Tarker scratched his chin absently. “Dangerous?” he repeated. He shrugged and said, “I do not think so, Mayt. But I suppose he did look like a battle-hardened warrior, I guess – if that is what you mean. Should I have not sent him to the Venom?” he asked, somewhat uncomfortable.<br>
<br>
“No, no,” Mayt reassured him. “I am sure he means no harm.” He forced a smile and bowed again. “Thank you for your time Master.” He turned and went out the door.<br>
<br>
As Mayt left the room, his mind was whirling with questions about the stranger. One thing he was sure of: the Erudite was a fighting man, and in these things he was himself poor. If his intuitions were correct regarding this man then he’d better work quickly and beat him back to his home. He couldn’t place what it was about the Erudite that made him nervous, but he knew for sure that he didn’t want the stranger reaching the Venom before he was there. If there was going to be trouble, he didn’t want his father defending his home by himself. What he needed, he thought, was some martial aid. Mayt was a skilled wizard, and a deadly foe, but when it came to arms and armor, he was as weak as a child. He immediately thought of his good friend Vaal, who was currently in Felwithe. If there was fighting to be done, Mayt wanted Vaal at his side. He broke into a jog toward the Paladin’s guild house where he knew he’d find him.<br>
<br>
 <p>Raff Phoenixheart
Librarian, Esprit d'Honneur
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uraffphoenixheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raff Phoenixheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#CC9900>(3/5/01 4:55:20 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   The Power Within 3</span><hr size=1> The Power Within 3<br>
<br>
The flickering light from the candles danced and fenced with the darkness, waging a private war of acquisition, at once advancing and losing ground, in a constant flux of territory. The mother lay on her back in the center of the room on a bed of silver silk sheets, her hair in disarray about her shoulders. Two midwives busied themselves around the mother in silence; words were unneeded between two women whose experience spanned more than thirty generations of Elven birthing.<br>
<br>
In the corner, as far away from the three women as possible so as not to get in their way, Tyle watched calmly as he strummed his lyre quietly. He marveled at how, even in the midst of childbirth, his wife could look so stunningly beautiful. Even with her legs splayed at awkward angles, her hair tousled and her belly swollen with child she was the most elegant woman he knew. His fingers moved effortlessly on the frets of his instrument but his eyes never strayed from his wife. Soon the pains of childbirth, along with the awkwardness and tension of the moment, would evaporate like cool rain on sun-baked rock and he would be a father. A father! He sighed deeply at the thought. This was to be the culmination of his life; he would have a son!<br>
<br>
Ghaiayna moaned quietly, her discomfort growing with every breath. Even Elven births could cause difficulty for the mother, although they had nowhere near the complications afflicting the lesser races. Tyle found himself grimacing slightly as his wife cried out, obviously in pain. Her body stiffened and her face was a mixture of pain and concentration. The Bard stopped his song and quickly began another, his fingers moving with expert grace along the strings. A warm glow of magical lights bathed the room and the four Elves as Tyle’s song surrounded them. Ghaiayna responded instantly to the magical music and relaxed visibly, her sweat-slicked body sinking back into the silk covered bed. The midwife at Ghaiayna’s head drew a moist cloth over the mother’s forehead and patted it along her cheeks and neck as she directed a small smile to Tyle, clearly approving his music.<br>
<br>
The woman at Ghaiayna’s feet whispered something to her, and a few moments later Tyle saw his wife straining. The time was near. He changed his tune slightly, adding a completely different set of notes to the song he was playing. The songs blended with each other smoothly, the new one sending a surge of strength and energy into his wife. She strained again, a small groan of exertion escaping her lips. Her hands clenched in fists and she lifted her back off the bed, pushing with the encouragement of the two midwives. Long moments later the second midwife announced with enthusiasm that she could see the baby’s head. The first midwife encouraged Ghaiayna to continue and grabbed her hands firmly in her own. The mother strained again, her entire body flexing rigidly, a long guttural grunt emanating from her lungs.<br>
<br>
Tyle stood and waited with rapt anticipation. He watched as the second midwife guided his child out of his wife’s body with practiced ease and gentleness. Seconds later his child forced breath into his lungs and expelled it with a shrill cry. Holding his lyre in one hand, he moved to his new son, his eyes sparkling with happiness. The midwife wrapped the child in a warm blanket and held him out for the Bard to hold. Tyle laid his lyre on the bed and accepted the child with open arms. He stared dumbfounded at the tiny, fragile being in his hands, staring amazedly at the child’s delicate hands as one wrapped around his finger. Carefully he moved to sit beside his wife and placed the baby in her arms. Ghaiayna held the newborn lovingly and kissed his head lightly. <br>
<br>
Tyle smiled broadly at his wife and leaned to kiss her. “My love, say hello to our new son.”<br>
<br>
Ghaiayna smiled dreamily and returned her husband’s kiss. “Hello Mayt,” she said quietly.<br>
 <p>Raff Phoenixheart
Librarian, Esprit d'Honneur
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uraffphoenixheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raff Phoenixheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#CC9900>(3/5/01 8:31:45 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   The Power Within 4</span><hr size=1> The Power Within 4<br>
<br>
“Mayt? No, but he should be back soon. Can I get something for you till he returns?” Ianarae’s voice was muffled, coming from behind the door.<br>
<br>
Mayt opened the door to the Venom quickly and burst into the inn with Vaal closely behind him. Inside he saw Ianarae standing before the tall erudite he had seen earlier that afternoon. His cloak was pulled back to reveal the massive sword on his hip, gripped lightly in his hand. They both turned toward the door when it opened. The erudite looked at Mayt with hard eyes as the he walked toward his wife. He gave Vaal a sidelong glance as Mayt put his arm protectively around Ianarae.<br>
<br>
“You must be Mayt,” the Erudite said, his voice low and serious.<br>
<br>
“Yes I am,” Mayt said and then looked over at Vaal who was walking slowly toward the group of three. Mayt had caught Vaal during afternoon arms practice and the Paladin had followed Mayt to the inn quickly without changing out of his battle armor. His friend was clothed from foot to neck in metal armor and he wore his prized sword “Ghoulbane” on his hip. As he approached the others, Vaal focused his stern gaze on the Erudite and calmly placed his hand on the pommel of his sword, matching the Erudite’s silent expression of power with his own. He stopped beside Mayt and turned to stare placidly at the tall man.<br>
<br>
“Have you met my good friend Vaal?” Mayt asked his voice slightly tense.<br>
<br>
The erudite bowed slightly toward Vaal and then Mayt. “It’s my pleasure to meet you finally Mayt,” he said, overtly avoiding any comment toward the Paladin. “My name is Emeroun, and I have been sent to find you.”<br>
<br>
“Find me?” Mayt said. He was taken aback; he didn’t expect the Erudite, or anyone else, to be looking for him.<br>
<br>
“I suppose you have accomplished that goal then. Why is it you, or anyone else, wishes to find me?”<br>
<br>
Emeroun’s eyes flickered to Vaal and then returned to Mayt. “I can’t really go into it right now, Mayt, but I need to take you back to Erudin as soon as possible. We must leave this day.”<br>
<br>
“What?” Mayt said, stunned. He looked at Ianarae who looked back at him with concern.<br>
<br>
Vaal cleared his throat and shifted his weight. “Nobody’s going anywhere at this time, Emeroun.” He crossed his arms on his chest to emphasize his point. Mayt smiled internally. When it came to being resolute, Vaal was unmatched.<br>
<br>
Emeroun scowled and paused, as if considering his next course of action. His face grew darker, and he worked his jaw slowly. Finally he spoke.<br>
<br>
“Fools! I don’t have time to stand around and argue with a bunch of stubborn Koada’dal!” <br>
<br>
He reached out to grab Mayt’s hand in his, but before he could reach the Wizard Vaal’s hand intercepted his. The Paladin held the man’s wrist tightly in his gauntleted fist and glared at him darkly. <br>
<br>
“I said, nobody’s going anywhere at this time. And I meant it!” He moved toward the man and stood mere inches from him, his hand still on Emeroun’s wrist. When he spoke his mouth barely opened. “Now you have two choices, Erudite. Either you can turn around and leave, or we can settle this the hard way.”<br>
<br>
Emeroun returned Vaal’s gaze silently with one equal in sternness.  The dark skin on his face rippled as he clenched his jaw, his fingers playing tentatively with the pommel of his sword. Finally, after many seconds of thick silence, he pulled his hand away from Vaal’s grip roughly and backed up. He tore his gaze from Vaal and glared at Mayt. He narrowed his eyes and spoke waveringly, through clenched teeth, obviously furious. “You will regret this, Koada’dal!” He then turned, whirling his cloak about him as he did, and strode quickly out of the inn.<br>
<br>
As soon as the door swung shut Ianarae grasped her husband in relief, holding him tightly. “What does he want from you?” She asked. <br>
<br>
Mayt looked at Vaal and sensed the same question in his friend’s eyes. He turned his eyes to the floor. “I have no idea,” he said weakly. “I just have no idea.”<br>
<br>
“Well, chances are he won’t be bothering you in the near future,” Vaal said. “But just to be safe, I think Lileah and I should stay here for a few days. If he does return, we’ll be here to change his mind.”<br>
<br>
Mayt smiled at his friend. He could always count on Vaal. “Vaal, I cannot thank you enough for coming here. Without your presence, I am not sure how this might have turned out.”<br>
<br>
Vaal chuckled. “I’m sure you would have done fine Mayt, but I’m glad I was here to help. You would have done the same for me.”<br>
<br>
Mayt smiled again and then looked around, fear flashing across his face. “Where is Maella?” he asked as he looked around the room. “Is she alright?”<br>
<br>
“I left her with her grandfather in the kitchen, Mayt,” Ianarae said. “I’m sure she’s fine.”<br>
<br>
Mayt hurried to the swinging doors that separated the common room from the kitchen and went through them as he called out his daughter’s name. “Maella? Where are you dear?”<br>
<br>
“Right here daddy,” she answered. “Grandpa made me some grape juice. Mayt found her in the kitchen sitting on a stool in front of the long table used to prepare food. Tyle was sitting across from her. They each had a glass of grape juice in front of them. His father looked at Mayt curiously.<br>
<br>
Mayt’s body sagged in relief as his wife entered the kitchen. It was times like these, when there was some imagined threat to his daughter, that he realized with clarity, how much she meant to him. His wife put a hand on his shoulder. <br>
<br>
“Mayt,” she said quietly, “let’s go downstairs to our room and talk about this Erudite with Vaal.”<br>
<br>
Mayt turned and nodded at his wife. As Ianarae followed him out into the common room she called over her shoulder, “We’ll be back in a few minutes Father. Then we can start to prepare for the evening crowd.”<br>
<br>
When they were downstairs in their room Ianarae looked at the two men and said, “I don’t know why, but I just get a bad feeling about this Emeroun. There’s something about him that makes me uncomfortable.”<br>
<br>
“I know dear. I do not trust him either,” Mayt said as he ran a hand through his hair nervously. “I overheard him having a conversation with Tarker Blazetoss while I walked through my guildhall. He wanted to know where I was, and when Master Tarker told him that I could be found at the Venom, I avoided him and ran to get Vaal.” <br>
<br>
“What did you hear Mayt? Did he say anything that might suggest why he wants you to go to Erudin?” Ianarae asked.<br>
 <br>
Mayt paused and thought a moment. “He asked a most strange question. He asked Master Tarker if I was the one who had trouble with control when I was younger.”<br>
<br>
Ianarae looked at Vaal to see if the information meant anything to him. Vaal just shrugged.<br>
<br>
“How odd,” she said. “What possible reason could an Erudite have interest in you because of your sickness?”<br>
<br>
“Maybe he’s studying a way to cause the sickness in others,” Vaal suggested. “There are many evil Necromancers in Paineel, and Tunare knows they are determined to destroy all the good in the world.”<br>
<br>
Mayt was shaking his head slowly. “I just cannot see why anyone would want to do that. It is not like it would cause anyone anything but pain and suffering.”<br>
<br>
Vaal folded his arms. “Maybe his goal is to cause more pain and suffering Mayt. Many people in this world have that as their main purpose in life.”<br>
<br>
Mayt sighed heavily and sat down on his bed, his eyes dropping to the floor. “I suppose you are right Vaal. I just never expected to be sought after because of some frailty that manifested itself in my childhood. I do suppose that it does still cause me great discomfort at times.”<br>
<br>
Ianarae sighed and put her hands on Mayt’s shoulders. “Don’t worry dear. We’ll make sure they don’t take you off to Erudin, even if they just want you to taste test the latest batch of brandy.”<br>
<br>
Vaal looked at Mayt, his face expressionless. “No, Mayt. We won’t.”<br>
