<br>
The day had been awful. Six hours ago the alarm had been raised throughout Kelethin, warning the Wood Elves that they were under attack. Mayt and his parents had been on their way to visit his aunt and uncle in the Wood Elf city. He always looked forward to the visits his family made to the city in the trees. His aunt, Airelil, always had delicious treats for him whenever he visited, and he always had fun playing with his cousin Lileah. His mother and father had been in high spirits as they made the journey through the Faydark to Kelethin, as they always were when they made the visits.<br>
<br>
But everything had gone wrong. Now Mayt was sitting in a large room in Felwithe with dozens of other High Elf children. He had been whisked away as soon as his parents heard the alarm sounding throughout the forest, and like the other children waiting in the room, he was tired, hungry and bored. The stone floor had ceased to be comfortable over four hours ago and there was nothing to do. Mayt had heard the word ‘Orcs’ mentioned quite a few times, but he didn’t really know much about orcs. The only thing he could remember was his mother telling him to ‘be good’ as she kissed him on the top of his head. He wasn’t entirely sure how he could be good right now, but he was trying his best. Initially only the older children seemed more upset than frustrated, but now most of the children had joined them in their concern and a sense of gloom had descended on the room. <br>
<br>
To worsen his mood, every few minutes someone he didn’t know would come into the room and call out one or more of the children, always from the same family, and take them away. Sometimes Mayt heard distant crying a few minutes after they were taken away, and it made him feel even more uncomfortable even though he didn’t even know why he felt so sad. At times he himself wanted to cry, but he didn’t know why. He wasn’t the only one; at least a quarter of the children in the room were crying or sniffling.<br>
 <br>
A young Wood Elf appeared in the doorway to the room and asked nervously, “Is Mayt here?” <br>
<br>
Mayt looked up from the stones he was sitting on and tentatively put up his hand. “I am Mayt,” he said, his voice weak from the tears fighting their way past his eyes.<br>
<br>
The Wood Elf approached Mayt slowly, a weak, forced smile on his face. He bent over at his waist when he was close to Mayt and spoke to him quietly. “Mayt? Are your parents Ghaiayna and Tyle?” He asked fidgeting nervously with his pant leg.<br>
<br>
Mayt was struck with an overwhelming sense of wrongness, as if the world had just done something very nasty, something mean. He looked at the Wood Elf with wide eyes and blinked a few times, his eyes watery with fear. “Yes. My father is Tyle and my mother is Ghaiayna.” Mayt blinked again. He was scared. He knew something was dreadfully wrong. He was too small for such a big world. He sniffled and remembered he was supposed to ‘be good’.<br>
<br>
The Wood Elf tried smiling again and barely managed the task. He reached down and offered his hand to Mayt. “My name is Pith. Could you come with me for a little walk, Mayt?” He asked softly.<br>
<br>
Mayt nodded quietly gave his hand to the other Elf and stood up slowly, his head spinning. His stomach was a giant knot. He let Pith lead him out of the room and down a long hall to a large open wooden door. The world seemed to be moving in slow motion, and the Wood Elf’s body blended in with the stone of the walls and the wood of the door. He felt himself being led into a small room where an older-looking High Elf male was sitting in a chair beside a female Wood Elf.<br>
<br>
“This is Mayt, Yeolorn.” Pith said. “His parents are Tyle and Ghaiayna.”<br>
<br>
The Elf named Yeolorn raised an eyebrow and looked at the woman beside him. “Then Kerean and Airelil are his uncle and aunt?”<br>
<br>
The Wood Elf female nodded at Yeolorn and then turned a soft, sad smile on Mayt. “How old are you Mayt?” she asked, her voice friendly.<br>
<br>
“Four.” He said. “Almost five now.” The tears came again, even though he was trying so hard to hold them back. He had to be good. His mother had told him to be good. Maybe he wasn’t supposed to cry. He tried harder.<br>
<br>
“My, my! You look like a big boy for your age!” she said.<br>
<br>
The world began to blur into a haze around Mayt. He was barely aware of the three adults in the room as they told him about the Orc raid on Kelethin, and the results of the battle. His head was spinning as Yeolorn told him his father was alive, but badly hurt, and that Tunare would look after him. He barely heard the woman speak over the rushing sound in his ears, and was numbly aware that his mother was dead, killed by an orc. He clenched his hands into tight little fists and listened quietly. Was it his fault that his mother had been hurt? He had tried to be good. The room was spinning faster and faster around him as she spoke and he only barely understood that his aunt, uncle and cousin were dead as well. A thick darkness filled his vision as the three of them explained that their sacrifice had saved Kelethin, and how they were heroes. <br>
<br>
His cheeks were wet with tears but he couldn’t see anyway as the darkness filled him. The room spun, then flipped and flopped, and he fell to the ground.<br>
<br>
He could barely feel the woman’s arms around him when she knelt beside him. He dimly heard her whisper “it’s ok”. <br>
<br>
Through tears he choked “I was good… I tried to be good.”<br>
<br>
He felt her arms tighten around him. She was shaking too, and he thought he heard her crying. Maybe her mother had been hurt too.<br>
<br>
