<br>
Three days after the strange Erudite had visited the inn, Mayt was cleaning up after the last few customers, wiping tables and carrying dishes back to the kitchen. The last customer had left half an hour ago and Mayt had sent the others to bed while he finished closing the Venom. He liked closing the inn because it was so peaceful at night. The common room seemed to hum with the after-glow of all the people who had been there during the evening. The people were gone, but, to Mayt, it seemed as though a part of their person had been left behind and it lingered for a few hours. He placed another two mugs from a table on top of the large tray he was carrying and started toward the kitchen. Just as he reached the swinging doors he heard the front door to the inn open. He continued into the kitchen to drop off the glasses and plates on his tray but when he heard the door close, followed by the sound of boots on the wooden floor, he called out from the kitchen.<br>
<br>
“I am sorry friend. We are closed for the night,” He shouted from behind the swinging doors. When there was no response he left his tray in the kitchen and went back into the common room, expecting to find a drunken customer looking for a final mug of ale before he went to bed. He passed the swinging doors and froze. There, in the middle of the common room, was Emeroun. His sword in hand, he was moving quietly toward the kitchen. Mayt found his voice and spoke loudly.<br>
<br>
“I said we are closed for the night Emeroun. You will have to leave now.”<br>
<br>
The Erudite continued toward Mayt, a snarl on his face. “I told you before that you had to come with me, and I wasn’t joking around and you WILL come with me now. I’ve sworn to bring you to Erudin, and I’ll be damned if some high and mighty Koada’dal is going to stop me.”<br>
<br>
Mayt flashed his hands through the complex movements of an attack spell as the man started toward him. If he could get off a spell quickly enough, he might survive. Emeroun broke into a run when he saw the wizard casting and was nearly on him when he was struck with the full fury of magical fire. As the fire tore at his skin, the Erudite cried out in pain, but he recovered quickly and raised his sword to strike at the High Elf. Mayt used the Erudite’s moment of indecision to quickly cast a mini-teleportation spell and was instantaneously moved across the room just as Emeroun’s sword crashed down on the spot he had been standing, rending one of the wooden swinging doors and ripping it off its hinges with a loud crash. Mayt realized with some surprise that the Erudite had directed the flat part of his blade at him. The realization that Emeroun wasn’t trying to kill him did little to comfort Mayt, however, and he began casting another attack spell as soon as he oriented himself after teleporting.<br>
<br>
With a grunt, the dark skinned warrior launched himself at Mayt, running two steps and then leaping across the remaining distance in an attempt to reach the wizard before he finished casting his spell. He struck Mayt squarely in his chest, knocking both of them to the floor. The Erudite scrambled up Mayt’s body till he had the Elf pinned to the ground, his hands on his shoulders. He was extremely strong and Mayt’s attempts to remove himself from his grasp were futile.<br>
<br>
“Now stop fighting me and I won’t have to smack you across the head,” he growled as he dropped his sword to the floor and grabbed both of Mayt’s wrists. Holding both of Mayt’s hands in his much larger left hand, the warrior reached to his hip with his right hand and pulled a rope from his belt. Mayt struggled impotently as his hands were bound together quickly. He tried squirming free by rolling on his stomach and felt a strong hand on his shoulder pulling him back. A moment later a loud crack rang out in the room and the Erudite fell off him to the side. <br>
<br>
Mayt scrambled off his stomach and sat up. There, standing above him, was Vaal, sword in hand, dressed in a sleeping shirt. The paladin took a quick look at his friend to make sure he was ok, and then moved to Emeroun who had fallen beside Mayt. Before he could move, the Erudite struck out with his armored boot, catching Vaal in the groin. Vaal gasped, releasing air from his lungs and bent slightly, stunned momentarily. He recovered a second later, but a second was all the warrior needed to place a second boot to Vaal’s knee, knocking the paladin off balance and causing him to fall backwards, landing on his Mayt.<br>
Emeroun wasted no time scrambling to his feet and using his enemy’s momentary disorientation to run from the inn. By the time Vaal was back to his feet, the Erudite was gone.<br>
<br>
Vaal grimaced and forced air back into his lungs, sitting down heavily beside Mayt. He reached for the rope around his friend’s hands and began untying it.  Mayt blinked Vaal with a look of surprise.<br>
<br>
“Thank you, again, my friend. You have doubtless saved my life.”<br>
<br>
Vaal scowled. “I did no such thing, and I let him get away.” Vaal was never one to accept a compliment. Once the rope was untied he stood up and leaned on a table. “Next time he won’t be so lucky. Next time I’ll be prepared.” He swore softly to himself.<br>
<br>
“He may have gotten away, Vaal, but I am still here, and I am very grateful for that.” He placed a hand on his friend’s shoulder. “He had my hands tied by the time you showed up. Twenty more seconds and I might have never seen you or my family ever again.” <br>
<br>
Vaal stood and offered Mayt a hand. The Wizard accepted it and got to his feet sluggishly. He reached behind his head and rubbed a tender spot.<br>
<br>
“Sweetheart? Is everything alright?” Ianarae was standing at the foot of the stairs with Lileah behind her. Both were wearing their nightclothes.<br>
<br>
Mayt tried to smile but failed. “Yes, dear. Thanks to Vaal.” Mayt looked over at his friend and noticed he had picked up Emeroun’s sword and was examining it closely, holding it in his hands. “Vaal managed to arrive at the most critical time and drive Emeroun off once again.”<br>
<br>
The women moved into the room and embraced their husbands, relieved to know they were alright. Lileah hugged Vaal and looked down at the sword in his hands. He seemed to be puzzled by it.<br>
<br>
“Vaal?” She said quietly. “What is so special about the sword?”<br>
<br>
Vaal jerked his head up from the blade. “What?” he said, distractedly.<br>
<br>
“The sword, dear,” Lileah smiled. “Why are you so interested in it?” She asked.<br>
<br>
Vaal turned and looked at Mayt. “This sword,” he said slowly, “is not a warrior’s sword.”<br>
<br>
Mayt tilted his head and furrowed his brow. “Not a warrior’s sword? Are you saying Emeroun is a foul Knight of Shadow?”<br>
<br>
Vaal shook his head slowly. “No,” he said simply. “This sword does not belong to a Shadow Knight.”<br>
<br>
Mayt looked around at the others, puzzled. Lileah and Ianarae looked just as confused as he felt. “Well then? If it is not a warrior’s blade, and not a Shadow Knight’s, then what kind of weapon is it?”<br>
<br>
Vaal looked across the room to the door the Erudite had fled through, his face thoughtful. “This is a Paladin’s weapon,” he said quietly.<br>
