“Now Mayt, you must be on your absolute best behavior while you’re with the Clerics.” Tyle said hoarsely. “Master Yeolorn has agreed to meet you and take you into the guild so that you may become a Cleric.”<br>
<br>
Mayt nodded quietly. “I will father,” he said, trying to remain calm and control his excitement.  They were standing just outside the Cleric guildhall, a few feet from the entrance. Tyle was on one knee before Mayt, his hands on his son’s shoulders.<br>
<br>
“Remember Mayt, your mother was a great Cleric, and so was your grandmother. You too will be a great Cleric,” Tyle said. His voice was forced and sounded painful.<br>
<br>
Mayt nodded again, his eyes darting around the guildhall entrance. Today he was going to be a Cleric! Ever since his father had recovered from his injury he constantly told Mayt that he was going to be a Cleric like his mother. His father had become obsessed with the idea over the three years since the battle at Kelethin. The damage to his throat was severe enough that no Cleric could heal him enough for him to regain his beautiful voice, thus ending his career as a songweaver. In response, Tyle had fallen into a deep depression lasting well over two years. As his savings dwindled his depression deepened, until finally, without any sign or warning, he snapped out of it. That day he left the small room in the inn that had been their home for the last year and went in search of a life. With the little money he had left he managed to work a deal to purchase the Venom. The next day he moved his son, hired a full staff and began his career as innkeeper.<br>
<br>
With his adventuring days officially over, Tyle yearned to live vicariously through Mayt, and started speaking of how he would one day become a great Cleric who would follow in his mother’s footsteps. For some reason, he never suggested that Mayt should become a Bard. Mayt wasn’t sure why. Maybe it was because he was only one-quarter Wood Elf unlike his father who was half Wood Elf. High Elves just don’t have the gift for music that their woodland cousins do. Most likely, though, it was Tyle’s desire to remember his deceased wife that drove him to make sure Mayt became a Cleric. At any rate, Tyle was convinced Mayt was going to be a great Cleric, and Mayt was quite happy to oblige him. He thought being a Cleric, having the power to heal and protect, would be fantastic. The adventure aspect of being a Cleric also attracted him, and he often daydreamed about defending Kelethin. In his mind’s eye he was there, fighting beside his father and mother, and when his mother fell against the Orcs, Mayt would cast a healing spell of great power and his mother would be restored and live. And when another Orc slashed his father’s throat, he would again cast a powerful healing spell, and save his father’s voice. At the end of the day, his family would march away from the field of battle, alive and well, and everyone who they saw would greet him and say ‘You must be a great Cleric, Mayt, to have kept both your parents alive’.<br>
<br>
Tyle stood up and took Mayt’s hand. He looked down at his son and smiled. “Are you ready, great Cleric?”<br>
<br>
Mayt didn’t look up at his father; his eyes were fixed on the door to the guildhall. “Yes, I am,” he said, nodding his head vigorously.<br>
<br>
Together they walked to the door of the guildhall, hand in hand. Tyle allowed Mayt to open the door, and he did. Before him lay the rest of his life.<br>
<br>
He was going to be a great Cleric!<br>
