<br>
Three weeks passed without a sign from the mysterious Erudite Paladin Emeroun, and it looked to Mayt like the issue was closed. Most likely, he thought, he was mortally embarrassed at being bested by a wizard and virtually naked paladin and losing his sword, and had returned to Erudin. In Mayt’s experience most Paladins had strange notions about honor and justice, so he was able to believe just about anything about the motivations of this odd Erudite Paladin.<br>
<br>
Maella was by his side, her hand in his, as they walked through the front gates of Felwithe into the Greater Faydark woods. Maella had been asking Mayt for over a week to take her back to see the Fay Drakes in the Lesser Faydark, and he had finally relented. At first he was concerned that Emeroun might show his face again, but that concern had evaporated a few days ago. Even Vaal, who was often paranoid about these things, had decided it was safe for him and Lileah to move out of the Venom and back to their small home. And so, that morning, when Maella once again asked if he could take her to the Fay Drakes, he had glanced at Ianarae for her approval. She had smiled and nodded, silently agreeing with Mayt that any danger was long gone.<br>
<br>
As they approached the massive stone teeth that served as a focus for Wizards when they teleported around Norrath, Maella was tugging excitedly at his hand, urging him to go faster.<br>
<br>
“Maella,” he smiled. “You must learn to be more patient dear.”<br>
<br>
She giggled and twisted around, bouncing in front of him happily. “I’m gonna see the Fay Drakes again,” she said in a sing-song voice.<br>
<br>
Mayt smiled at his daughter and bent to speak with her, hoping to calm her just a bit so he could get her to the Drakes with less trouble. He didn’t want her running off in excitement.<br>
<br>
“Maella, sweetheart,” he said calmly, “daddy needs you to –“<br>
<br>
“I’ll send you to your god, worthless scum!” a rough voice growled from Mayt’s right. He snapped his head toward the sound and was instantly filled with dread when he saw Emeroun bolting from behind one of the Wizard spires, charging toward him and Maella, a sword drawn in his hand. His face was twisted in a snarl of anger and hatred, a look Mayt had never seen on the Erudite before. <br>
<br>
Mayt instantly released Maella’s hand and cast a rooting spell on the charging Erudite. The spell went off just before Emeroun reached Mayt, holding the large man firmly to the ground. Emeroun snarled and spat as he tried desperately to break free from the magical bonds holding him to the ground.<br>
<br>
“Stupid High Elf fool!” He raged. “In god’s name get out of the way!” His eyes were drawn to small slits and they focused past Mayt.<br>
<br>
Mayt’s stomach flopped and fear gripped at his chest as he realized someone was behind him. Emeroun wasn’t trying to attack him - he was after someone else! He whirled around, preparing to cast another spell of rooting but came face to face with the leering soulless eyes of a skeleton. With a hideous cackle the skeleton swung a bony fist at the Wizard, catching him squarely on the side of his head before he could complete his spell. He fell to the ground, stunned, his vision filled with floating sparks of light. As he heard his daughter scream in fear, he felt another blow land on his head, and the world winked out in darkness.<br>
