<br>
Mayt sat quietly in the large chair, staring intently at his soft leather shoes. He wasn’t looking forward to this meeting. For the last five years he’d been working as hard as possible to be the best Cleric he could be, and now, he was going to be a failure. At twelve years old he should be starting to master the basic magic spells, but no matter how hard he tried he was completely unable to call forth magic. He thought of his father, and how disappointed he would be when he found out his son wasn’t going to be a Cleric. All Mayt could remember of his life was his desire, no, his destiny, to be a Cleric in the service of Tunare and Felwithe. He desperately fought back the tears threatening to fill his eyes.<br>
<br>
The door opened softly and Master Yeolorn entered followed closely by Tyle. Mayt couldn’t make himself look at his father, afraid to see his face, to feel his shame.<br>
<br>
“It is good of you to come to see us, Tyle. I know your inn keeps you busy,” Yeolorn said as he walked toward his desk. He indicated the chair beside Mayt with his hand. “Please sit and make yourself comfortable, my friend.”<br>
<br>
Tyle sat down casually. “I can always make time for Tunare’s Clerics, Master Yeolorn,” he said, his voice a loud whisper. He smiled and ran his hands along the armrests of the chair. “I trust everything is alright?” He looked over at Mayt. When his son didn’t look back at him, he frowned. “Or maybe there is something wrong?” He looked at Yeolorn and his frown deepened. “Has Mayt done something that requires correction? If so, I can assure you I will support any methods you need to use to correct his behavior.”<br>
<br>
Master Yeolorn returned the frown and sighed deeply as he sat down heavily. “I am afraid we have a difficult situation, Tyle.”<br>
<br>
Tyle looked at Mayt and then back to Yeolorn, his face darkening with anger. “What has my son done?” Tyle’s words sounded bitter in his sibilant voice. “If he has been disrespectful in any way, I’ll make sure - ”<br>
<br>
Master Yeolorn interrupted Tyle by holding up his hand and shook his head. “Tyle, your son has been nothing but an exemplary student. He has worked harder than any other in training. He has never misspoken, he has always been respectful, always articulate, and in all ways a model student.” He laid his hands on the desk, palms down. “I want to make this perfectly clear, Tyle: Mayt had done nothing wrong.”<br>
<br>
Mayt sighed internally. At least Master Yeolorn’s kind words of praise would lessen his father’s embarrassment.<br>
<br>
Tyle glanced between Yeolorn and Mayt, confusion spreading across his face. “But then…” he began, his voice strained. “I’m afraid I don’t understand, Master Yeorlorn. If he has been a model student, then what is the problem?”<br>
<br>
“Mayt is at the age where his magical powers should be manifesting themselves. As he grows into adulthood, his powers will grow, and it was our intention to direct their growth in such a way that he can serve The Mother of All.” Yeolorn looked at Mayt and frowned. “Unfortunately, even though Mayt has, as I said earlier, been a model student, and in all ways strived to learn what we teach, he does not seem able to grasp even the simplest of healing spells.”<br>
<br>
A look of shock flashed across Tyle’s face. “Then my son has no magic in him? How is that possible? His mother - his grandmother - they were both great Healers. Even I have the ability to weave magic into my songs. Magic absolutely proliferates through this family from generation to generation.” His hoarse voice was raspy with emotion. “My son cannot be magically inert! It is not possible!”<br>
<br>
Mayt bit his lip hard, fighting to stem the flow of tears.<br>
<br>
“No, Tyle, you are correct,” Yeorlorn replied. “Magic does indeed flow through your family, including Mayt. There is no doubt that he has come of age and his body is awakening in power. In fact, we have detected power in Mayt that is much stronger than we would expect to see in any Elf his age. Make no doubt about it: Mayt has the power of magic running through his blood.”<br>
<br>
Tyle narrowed his eyes in confusion. “Well, then, what is the problem? If Mayt has the power, and he is a good student -” He stopped, obviously unable to find the words.<br>
<br>
Yeorlorn sighed. “It is a most unusual thing, Tyle. Mayt has power, and he works at his spells harder than any student. I am sure it must be exceedingly frustrating for him, and yet he continues, day after day, struggling to bring forth the energy that courses through him.” He ran a hand across his brow and breathed deeply. “For some reason, one we cannot determine, he is completely unable to cast even the simplest spells, even though he performs the actions necessary with complete accuracy.” Yeorlorn clasped his hands together and leaned forward on his desk. “For all we know and understand, Mayt should be releasing his energy and the spells he tries to cast should be successful. But, no matter what he does, the spells never manifest themselves as they should. In fact, nothing whatsoever happens. If we didn’t know better, I would assume Mayt was without magic.”  <br>
<br>
Yeolorn paused and watched Tyle for a reaction. The old Bard stared dumbfounded at the Cleric, shaking his head slowly.<br>
<br>
“Then what is to be done?” Tyle asked after a few moments of uncomfortable silence.<br>
<br>
Yeolorn looked up at the ceiling and sighed deeply. He slowly brought his head down to look at Tyle again. “At this time, Tyle, all we can suggest is that Mayt return home with you.” He shrugged slightly. “The hard truth is, Mayt is taking the place of other young Clerics who need our time and training. Even though I would dearly like to have Mayt join the ranks of Tunare’s Healers, I see no possible way for this to happen.” He paused to observe Tyle’s reaction. “This has been a concern for over a year now, I fear. Please know, Tyle, this decision has not been made lightly.”<br>
<br>
Tyle nodded wordlessly, his eyes on the floor. He was silent for long moments and then finally spoke. “When?” he asked simply.<br>
<br>
Yeolorn looked at Mayt with obvious sadness. “Today. There is no need to keep him here any longer.”<br>
<br>
Tyle immediately rose and reached for Mayt’s hand. “Come Mayt. You can learn to wash dishes with me,” he said, his throaty voice thick with bitterness.<br>
<br>
Mayt stood and followed his father as he walked to the door leading from the room. His face was wet with tears. Inside him, shame burned hotly, and he wished he could just disappear from the world. As Tyle placed his hand on the doorknob Yeolorn stood.<br>
<br>
“Tyle,” he said quietly.<br>
<br>
Tyle turned from the door to face the Cleric. “Yes?” he said caustically.<br>
<br>
“Tyle, remember, this is not Mayt’s fault,” Yeolorn said softly. “He has done everything he could possibly do. There is no shame in this for him, or for your family.”<br>
<br>
Tyle snarled. “I’ll be the judge of what shames my family. Not you.” He glared at Yeolorn with dark eyes. “Is that all?”<br>
<br>
Yeolorn closed his eyes and nodded. “Yes,” he said. “Goodbye Mayt. I wish you well.”<br>
<br>
Mayt tried to answer his teacher, but the words caught in his throat as Tyle pulled him down the hallway. A moment later the door closed behind him, forever ending his dreams of being a Cleric.<br>
