<br>
“Excuse me?” A young Wood Elf was standing in the entrance of the Venom, looking around the inn nervously.<br>
<br>
“Come in and have a seat,” Ianarae said as she was bent over wiping one of the empty tables. “I’ll be with you in a moment friend.”<br>
<br>
“Is there an Ianarae here?” he asked timidly.<br>
<br>
Ianarae stopped wiping the table and stood, smiling. “Yes there is. I’m her.” She dropped her washcloth on the tray resting on a nearby table and walked over to meet him. “What can I do for you?” she asked.<br>
<br>
“I was out walking in the Faydark,” he began falteringly, “well, I was just looking for some berries to use for making some wine, and well-“<br>
<br>
“Is something wrong?” Ianarae asked. She really didn’t have to ask the question because she was sure something was wrong. Just by the way the young Elf was talking she could tell he had some sort of bad news. Her mind started flashing through all the possibilities. Was Tyle alright? He had just left to get some supplies minutes ago. Or Mayt? Or Maella? Her husband had just left a few hours ago to take their daughter for a walk in the Lesser Faydark.<br>
<br>
“Well – uh, yes, I suppose there might be something wrong.” <br>
<br>
He looked dreadfully embarrassed, a condition that did nothing to calm Ianarae. She figured if she was going to get anything meaningful out of him, she had better get him under control. A throbbing fear had started to develop in her stomach, but she fought it down. This Elf wouldn’t be much good to her if he thought she was upset. She took his hand in hers gently.<br>
<br>
“What was your name?” She said with forced cheerfulness.<br>
<br>
“Poular, my lady. My name is Poular.”<br>
<br>
“Well, Poular,” she smiled, “why don’t you come over here and have a seat.” She guided him to a nearby table and he sat down awkwardly. She sat across from him and smiled in a way she hoped was comforting. <br>
<br>
“Now, what do you have to tell me?”<br>
<br>
Poular looked down at the table. “Is your husband Mayt?” he asked. “Mayt, the Wizard?”<br>
<br>
Ianarae fought to remain calm. Mayt had been hurt. She was sure of it, and she was sure it was Emeroun who had hurt him. He’d found him after sneaking around for the last few weeks. She remembered he was a Paladin, according to Vaal and her fear blossomed to anger.<br>
 <br>
“Yes,” she said through tight lips. “Mayt is my husband, and he’s a Wizard. Why do you ask?” She couldn’t decide whether to cry or scream. No, on second thought, she wanted to hit someone. If Emeroun had taken her husband all the way to Erudin then she would find him and make him pay dearly. And if Maella was just left there, without an escort back home… Her thoughts were interrupted by Poular.<br>
<br>
“Well, uhh, I saw Mayt, that is, he … he was attacked today.” Poular said stutteringly. “At the Wizard spires just outside Lesser Fay,” he added.<br>
<br>
Ianarae’s anger solidified. It was Emeroun, with his stupid paladin plan to take Mayt back to Erudin for some stupid  reason and she was going to go there herself and smack him over the head with her staff. She almost smiled at the thought.<br>
<br>
“Was he an Erudite?” she asked, almost pleased with herself to see the look of surprise on the Wood Elf’s face.<br>
<br>
“Yes … yes he was!” Poular said with surprise. “How did you know?”<br>
<br>
Ianarae rolled her eyes. “He was threatening to take Mayt back to Erudin a few weeks ago. We thought he’d left, but obviously we were wrong. And now, when I find him, I’m going to smack him over the head with my staff.” She looked somewhat happy at the thought. Poular shrunk back in his chair, obviously a bit concerned over Ianarae’s reaction.<br>
<br>
“So, it isn’t much to be concerned about?” he asked, taken aback.<br>
<br>
“Oh, it’s something to be concerned about alright.” She narrowed her eyes. “Especially if you’re an Erudite Paladin named Emeroun.” Paladins may be honest and only motivated by good and righteous reasons, but they could be so infuriatingly stubborn often, especially once they had an idea in their head. They were like boiled-down distillations of male stubbornness.<br>
<br>
Poular looked immensely confused. He stared at Ianarae for a long moment as if trying to determine whether she was serious. Or maybe insane.<br>
<br>
“Does that mean you’re not afraid for Mayt or your daughter?” he asked with hesitation.<br>
<br>
Ianarae looked back at the Wood Elf as the color drained from her face. “My daughter?” she said quietly, her voice nearly a whisper. “What about my daughter? I had assumed that…”<br>
<br>
Poular swallowed uncomfortably. “Well, my lady, your daughter was there, and –“<br>
<br>
Ianarae’s whimsical anger shot instantly to boiling fury. She stood up, pressing her hands on the table and shouted: “What? My daughter? That Erudite Paladin fool TOOK MY DAUGHTER!?”<br>
<br>
Poular almost fell backwards in his chair “Yes, my lady. I’m sorry. I didn’t mean to mislead you.” He stammered as he stood and backed a few steps away from her.<br>
<br>
Ianarae was furious. It was one thing to involve her husband in some silly Paladin journey, but it was completely another to put a child at risk. When she caught Emeroun she was going to make him pay. Her mind was jumbled with thoughts and images of her daughter taken on some long senseless journey across Norrath.<br>
<br>
At that moment the door of the inn opened and Emeroun walked in, a surly expression on his dark face. Ianarae glared and pointed her finger at him. She felt some relief knowing he was still in Felwithe. That meant Maella was probably nearby, and safe. Relief or not, though, she was still furious.<br>
<br>
“How dare you show your face in this place!” She stomped around the table and toward the Erudite, her hand waving in admonishment. “It is one thing to take my husband on some silly Paladin expedition to Erudin, but it’s an entirely different thing when you take my baby girl.” <br>
<br>
She walked directly up to him and pointed her finger into his chest, almost at the level of her eyes. He looked down at her with a mixture of anger and confusion while she tapped her finger into his chest, emphasizing every word she said.<br>
<br>
“You will immediately go get my daughter, and return her, instantaneously back to me, and I don’t want to hear any stupid Paladin arguments about how you have to do this, or you have to do that.”<br>
<br>
“Uh… my lady?” Poular said weakly from behind her.<br>
<br>
“I don’t mean now, mister Paladin, I mean RIGHT now! You may think you’re tough, but you do NOT want to mess with an angry mother!”<br>
<br>
“Lady Ianarae? I think that maybe, uh…” Poular said with hesitation.<br>
<br>
“What?” she said venomously as she whirled around to face the Wood Elf. “If you’re going to say something, say it! Stop babbling!”<br>
<br>
“Well… that’s not the Erudite who took Mayt.”<br>
<br>
“What?” she said, stunned. “What do you mean? This is Emeroun.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, of course, my lady, I’m sure he is, and all, but, well… he’s not the person who attacked Mayt.”<br>
<br>
Ianarae’s mouth moved silently as she tried to work this new information into her brain. He mind whirled as she tried to grasp the situation. She turned back to Emeroun dazedly. She felt as if the world was crashing around her. If Emeroun wasn’t the Erudite, then who took Mayt? And where? And where was Maella? She forced herself to speak.<br>
<br>
“What happened? If you didn’t take Mayt and Maella, then … then who did?”<br>
<br>
Emeroun frowned. “There is much to discuss Ianarae. I think we should gather your friends. I have a feeling we’re going to need them.”<br>
<br>
<br>
