The platter of food fell to the floor with a loud crash.<br>
<br>
“Mayt!” Tyle rasped. “Be careful! I cannot afford to have you dumping good food on the floor!”<br>
<br>
Mayt had been carrying the tray out of the kitchen to one of the customers a moment before the pain hit him. Now he was on his knees with a tray of food spread around him on the floor.<br>
<br>
“Mayt! Get up and clean up that mess! Hurry!” his father croaked in anger.<br>
<br>
Mayt struggled to get to his feet, but he had no strength in his legs, and they didn’t seem to want to lift him up. Liquid fire was raging through his body and he felt like his insides had been thrown into a bucket of boiling water. Every inch of his body was inflamed with burning pain. He gasped for air desperately, but his lungs wouldn’t work either. All he was able to do was emit a weak choking sound.<br>
<br>
“Mayt!” his father repeated firmly. Mayt tried to respond, but even his limbs refused to obey him and he simply stayed there, on his knees, unmoving. He knew his father was angry, but that wasn’t new. In the last two weeks since he left the Cleric’s guild his father had been exceedingly harsh with him. He didn’t blame him, really. After all, Mayt thought, he was a failure. His father wasn’t a bard anymore, but at least he had a reason for his inability; he had lost his voice to an Orc’s foul weapon. Mayt had no such excuse. His father was right; he was a failure. Even so, he didn’t want to give his father any reason to be angry, but he still couldn’t move. He heard his father pulling bowls down from one of the cupboards and he tried to gather his strength.<br>
<br>
Slowly the pain started to subside, leaving his fingers and toes first, and then working its way out of his limbs toward his chest, where it always seemed to center. Although his father was unaware, this wasn’t the first time he’d been struck by the pain. In fact, he had felt the pain every night for the last week. It would come a few hours after he went to sleep, waking him up. Sometimes it was worse than other times, but it had always been at night, and at night he could just lay in bed quietly, crying softly, but disturbing no one. This was different. This he couldn’t hide. He started moving to his feet slowly, using the nearby counter for support.<br>
<br>
“Mayt?” His father’s voice was softer now, a spark of concern in it. Mayt was surprised to hear his father so close to him. “Mayt, are you alright?”<br>
<br>
“Yes father,” Mayt managed. He had to force the words out. He felt his father’s hand on his shoulder.<br>
<br>
“What happened?” Tyle asked. “Did you trip?”<br>
<br>
Mayt just shook his head. “I am alright father. It will pass momentarily.”<br>
<br>
“It will pass? What will pass? Did you hurt yourself?”<br>
<br>
Mayt grimaced as the pain flickered in his chest, nearly spent now. “No, I just had a pain, that is all.”<br>
<br>
Tyle looked at Mayt carefully. “A pain? What kind of a pain?”<br>
<br>
“It is nothing, father. I am sorry I spilled the food.” He ran a hand through his hair.<br>
<br>
“What caused the pain, Mayt?” Tyle asked, his voice tense.<br>
<br>
“Nothing, father. I am alright now.”<br>
<br>
“What do you mean nothing? You can’t just have pains with no reason son. What caused this pain?”<br>
<br>
Mayt shrugged slightly, still not looking at his father. “I do not know what causes them father.”<br>
<br>
Tyle turned his son’s face toward him gently. When Mayt looked at him, he saw pain and fear in the young boy’s light blue eyes. “How long have you had these pains?”<br>
<br>
“I am not sure. Perhaps a couple of weeks. It has only bothered me at nights,” he said and then added: “Well, that is, until this moment.”<br>
<br>
“Perhaps we should take you to see the Clerics Mayt.”<br>
<br>
The young boy turned his head away from his father. “No, father. I am sure it is nothing. I do not want to go back to the Clerics. I do not deserve to go there.”<br>
<br>
A look of pain flashed across Tyle’s face. “Well, please let me know if it happens again, Mayt. I don’t want you to go through pain unnecessarily. If something can be done for you, then it should be done. And the sooner the better.”<br>
<br>
Mayt nodded slowly. “Alright, father I will. I am sure that it is just –“<br>
<br>
Mayt gasped and slammed his eyes shut before finishing the sentence. Fire erupted through his body and he grabbed the counter top to hold himself up, leaning heavily against it. A second wave of pain shot through him, reaching his legs, and he fell to the floor again. He tried to stand up but agony ripped through him again, this wave more powerful than the first two. It felt like long steel daggers were driving through his body, from his chest out to his limbs and into his head. He curled up into a ball and moaned softly.<br>
<br>
“Mayt!” his father cried hoarsely.<br>
<br>
His body convulsed involuntarily as a fourth explosion raced through his entire body. He thought he must be on fire. He exhaled all the air from his lungs as every muscle in his body was stretched tight. His back arched off the floor awkwardly and he screamed. Slowly he felt his mind going dark, inexorably, one bit of his consciousness at a time. The pain shot through him again and again, unceasing, and he blacked out.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
“Mayt?” he heard a soft voice, far away, calling him. “Mayt? Are you awake?” <br>
<br>
The voice seemed familiar, but he couldn’t place it. He tried to open his eyes, but found them stuck fast. He tried to speak but his mouth wouldn’t open.<br>
<br>
“Mayt, it’s ok.” The voice said again. “Everything is ok. You’re in the Cleric’s guild now, and we’re taking care of you. You’re going to be fine.” <br>
<br>
The voice belonged to a woman. One of the Clerics, he thought. He was pretty sure she was a younger member.<br>
<br>
“My name is Filianya, Mayt. Do you remember me?” He voice was calm and soothing. He tried to speak again, concentrating as hard as he could on making his mouth move.<br>
<br>
“Don’t worry about speaking if you don’t want to. You need to conserve your strength so you can get better.”<br>
<br>
He tried to speak again. His lips felt like frozen lead.<br>
<br>
“What happened? Is that what you asked? Oh Mayt, we’re not quite sure. All we know is what your father told us. You have been suffering from pains lately, and they were strong enough today to make you black out. Don’t worry Mayt. You just relax.” He could feel her hand on his forehead. “I’ll be nearby if you need me, but for now, just get some sleep Mayt.” A few seconds later he fell asleep again.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Tyle and Yeolorn were standing a few feet from Mayt’s bed. Tyle was looking at his son lying in the bed, unable to talk, obviously in a great deal of pain. The young Cleric Filianya was sitting on the bed beside Mayt, washing his forehead with a damp cloth. He looked back at Yeolorn with concern.<br>
<br>
“Have you ever heard of anything like this before, Master Yeolorn?”<br>
<br>
Yeolorn shook his head sadly and sighed. “No, Tyle, I have not. In all my years as a healer, I have never seen something as strange as this. Mayt seems to be fine in all ways, but something is causing him a great deal of discomfort.”<br>
<br>
“Pain would be a better description, I think,” said Tyle as he looked over at his son again.<br>
<br>
Yeolorn nodded in agreement. “Yes, pain is indeed a good description. What concerns me the most is that he has been in this state since you brought him here, three days ago. His condition has not changed. In fact, if anything, I would say his pain has increased.” Yeolorn shook his head again. “I fear that if something does not change soon, he will not last much longer.”<br>
<br>
“Is there nothing you can do for him?” Tyle asked<br>
<br>
“No, we have tried all we know. We must wait for Tunare to heal him now.” Yeolorn put his hand on Tyle’s shoulder comfortingly. We will continue to watch over him, Tyle, and if anything changes, we will be sure to let you know as soon as –“<br>
<br>
Filianya cried out in pain and fell to the floor. Both men snapped their heads in the direction of the noise and started toward the young Cleric, who was lying on the floor, unmoving. As Yeolorn reached her side he knelt down and examined her. Tyle could smell burned fabric and noticed that Filianya’s robe was singed in places. <br>
<br>
Yeolorn looked up at Tyle in confusion. “She has been hurt. Quite badly, I am afraid but I can heal her easily enough.” He pressed his hands to her head and shoulder carefully. Tyle could sense magic around him as Yeolorn cast a simple spell of healing. A moment later the young Cleric’s eyes fluttered open and she sat up weakly and looked at Tyle and Yeolorn, a thoroughly confused look on her face.<br>
<br>
“What happened?” she asked in a daze.<br>
<br>
“You were hurt, Filianya. Your robe is burned. I was hoping you could answer that question for us.”<br>
<br>
“Master Yeolorn? Father? Why am I in the infirmary?” a confused voice asked quietly.<br>
<br>
The three of them turned to the voice in surprise. Two feet from them Mayt was sitting up in bed, a confused expression on his face. Tyle thought he saw fear in his son’s eyes but he didn’t look like he was in pain anymore. In fact, he was sitting up in bed, looking as though he had just awoken from a long comfortable sleep.<br>
<br>
“Mayt?” Tyle said cautiously, as if speaking too harshly would cause his son to fall into another apoplexy. “Are you all right, son?”<br>
<br>
Mayt looked around dazedly. “I think so Father. I feel … strange. Odd.”<br>
<br>
Yeolorn put his hand on Tyle’s arm lightly. “Tyle,” he said. “What color are your son’s eyes.<br>
<br>
“Blue,” Tyle said and then looked at his son’s eyes reflexively.<br>
<br>
Mayt looked back at his father, puzzlement showing clearly in his dark red eyes.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
