The Power Within 12<br>
<br>
Deepness. <br>
<br>
Darkness.<br>
<br>
The world was spinning, turning.<br>
<br>
Blackness.<br>
<br>
And then, a light. <br>
<br>
Far above. <br>
<br>
He willed his hand up. Reaching toward it. Struggling to break free. The air was thick pitch. He was sinking fast. His hand reached higher, reached toward the light.<br>
<br>
The light. He struggled harder, bending his mind to the task. Pain stabbed through his head, but he concentrated past it. He had to reach the light.<br>
<br>
The light was nearer. The sound of rushing water raced past his ears. Building. Roaring as the light crept closer.<br>
<br>
The rushing built, louder and louder. The light neared. He pulled with all his might, drove his will toward the light. <br>
<br>
Up. <br>
<br>
Out. Must get out!<br>
<br>
His ears filled with a cacophony of roaring voices, shouting.<br>
<br>
The light erupted and consumed him and he was awake.<br>
<br>
He coughed, gasping for air and jerked upward, trying to sit up. His wrists wouldn’t move and they held his body back and he slumped back to the hard stone beneath him. The thick smell of damp stone filled his nostrils and his eyes flickered open, tentatively. The light rammed itself into his head, driving his eyes closed and he groaned and turned his head away. He breathed again and his body was rent with racking coughs. Again he tried to sit up, and again he was unable to. Something was holding his wrists down. He heard the dull clanking of heavy chains.<br>
<br>
He lay there quietly, his body both numb and in pain at the same time. Gradually he slowed his breathing and managed to calm himself. Again he opened his eyes, this time allowing them to form tiny slits, fearing the light. Again pain drove through his head, but this time he willed his eyes to remain open. As his eyes became accustomed to the dim light, he allowed his mind to evaluate his surroundings.<br>
<br>
Somewhere distant he could hear running water, and behind it, sensed more than heard, was the low thrum of magic. Through vision that remained stubbornly fuzzy he looked at the ceiling, and noted its old stonework. He heard a rat squeak echo off the wet stony walls, suggesting the room was fairly large. As he strained to hear he became aware of a soft, barely audible sniffling coming from his right. There was something odd about it – something strangely familiar. He turned his head tenderly to his right and opened his eyes wider, grunting in pain as he did.<br>
<br>
When his eyes could focus he saw a small figure laying on what looked to be a stone altar. The pain built as he strained to open his eyes wider to see the person clearly. It was a little girl, he supposed, and she was crying softly. He blinked his eyes painfully and the room began to spin again. Immediately he snapped them shut, fighting down the nausea that leapt to his throat. Swallowing with difficulty, he licked his lips and tried to speak.<br>
<br>
“Maella?” he said, barely audible. After a few moments with no response, her repeated the question with more force.<br>
<br>
“Maella?” he repeated. Pain shot through his head again, and his stomach lurched. He turned his face up, hoping he would not vomit.<br>
<br>
“Daddy?” the girl sniffled.<br>
<br>
The dizziness overtook him as he tried to respond. He had to tell his daughter he was there. He had to let her know everything was going to be all right, but his tongue was thick and immobile. A rushing sound started in his ears as he tried to speak, building to a crescendo just as the darkness overtook him again.<br>
