“When will they arrive?” Tyle whispered to Yeolorn.<br>
<br>
“Soon. I sent for them this morning.”<br>
<br>
Tyle nodded. After the last strange illness, and the bizarre way Mayt cured himself, his son seemed to return to normal. He went home to the Venom that afternoon and acted as if nothing had happened. Yeolorn suggested that Mayt was suffering from some form of adolescent mana manifestation, but he couldn’t offer any good explanations or even suggestions for the young Elf. Tyle had simply taken Mayt home and hoped the event would never replay itself. However, against his hopes, two weeks later Mayt started to feel the pain again, and within two days of it starting he had to bring his son back to Yeolorn. This time the illness had taken Mayt rapidly, and within two days of the first pains he was completely incoherent and bedridden. This time, the pain seemed to be greater, and Mayt was tossing and turning fitfully in his bed. For the safety of the clerics, Yeolorn didn’t let any younger, less experienced ones go near Mayt. He wanted to avoid a more severe magical out burst.<br>
<br>
That morning, Mayt had not awoken, and seemed to be in far greater pain than the last time, and Yeolorn had suggested to Tyle that they send for a Wizard to come and examine Mayt, since the type of magic manifested by Mayt appeared to be the type controlled and channeled by Wizards. Tyle had agreed easily, hoping for any solution and any ideas from any source. Now he was waiting impatiently for the Wizard to arrive.<br>
<br>
Tyle wrung his hands nervously and looked at his son across the room tossing fitfully in his bed. Every few seconds Mayt’s head would turn from one side to the other, and he would emit a small groan. Occasionally the young Elf’s body would stiffen and spasm, obviously in great pain. Tyle felt Yeolorn’s hand on his shoulder and he put his own on top of the Cleric’s wrinkled hand.<br>
<br>
“Do not worry Tyle,” Yeolorn said soothingly. “Mayt survived the last episode, and I’m sure he’ll survive this one.”<br>
<br>
Tyle wasn’t so sure. As far as he could tell, his son was slipping closer and closer to death with each new spasm. The last time Mayt had released his energy much earlier than this. The last time it had taken months for the illness to build to this point. And it had never been this bad the first time either. No, Tyle was convinced that the Wizard’s were Mayt’s last hope, and that if they couldn’t help him, then nobody could, and soon he’d be burying his son. He shook his head and tried to ignore that horrible possibility.<br>
<br>
Time seemed to creep along for Tyle. As he watched his son toss and turn, he could feel a part of his pain. Yeolorn left and returned, twice, but neither time did he bring someone with him. The old bard paced slowly across the stones, tapping his hand impatiently against his thigh. When the pacing became tedious he looked out the only window in the dreary room, hoping to catch sight of a robed figure, someone from the Wizard’s guild coming to help his son, but the sky had turned overcast, and soon after, the dark gray clouds released a gentle spray. He returned to pacing, once again desperately trying to think of something other than Mayt and his illness.<br>
<br>
A footstep behind him snapped his attention back to the world and he turned around quickly to greet the visitor.<br>
<br>
“Tyle, this Dalmariv, one of the Wizards in Felwithe. He’s here to see your son.” Yeolorn smiled slightly. “Dalmariv, this is Tyle, father of our young patient.”<br>
<br>
Tyle bowed deeply. “I’m most relieved to have you here, Dalmariv. My son is quite ill, and I fear you may be the last hope he has,” Tyle said as he watched the robed figure carefully. Dalmariv merely inclined his head toward Tyle, remaining silent. He was covered from head to toe in a dark blue flowing robe. Intricate patterns interwove amongst themselves across the chest and down the arms of the robe. He couldn’t make out the Wizard’s face from behind the deep hood he was wearing, and this did little to comfort him. Tyle watched Dalmariv as he walked past him mutely and approached Mayt’s bed. He was about to speak, but Yeolorn’s hand on his shoulder kept him silent.<br>
<br>
<br>
As the Wizard reached Mayt’s bed, he slowly removed the deep cowl from his head and laid the hood lightly upon his back. To Tyle’s surprise, his skin was dark, with a darker patch of curly hair upon it. He looked to Yeolorn curiously.<br>
<br>
Yeolorn sensed the unspoken question and whispered a response. “He is here to study with the Koada’Dal, and to share knowledge from his people, and I understand he is an accomplished Wizard. Do not fear Tyle.” He smiled reassuringly at Tyle.<br>
<br>
Tyle looked back to the Erudite who had lightly placed his left hand onto Mayt’s forehead. His right hand remained above the young Elf’s body, hovering there, as if floating on some unseen force emanating from Mayt’s body. He closed his eyes and spoke a few quiet words. At once Mayt’s body jerked violently and Dalmariv was surrounded by gouts of flame so hot Tyle could feel their heat from fifteen feet away. The Erudite staggered but regained his calm with remarkable ease. Tyle noticed immediately that Mayt was breathing easier, and he could tell his son was no longer in pain. Instead of relief, however, he felt a profound sense of puzzlement and looked on at the Erudite with confusion showing clearly in his face. Dalmariv pulled the large cowl back onto his head and walked calmly toward the two Elves.<br>
<br>
When he spoke, his voice was rich yet clear, even though he spoke barely above a whisper. “Master Yeolorn, is there a room where we might speak and not disturb the boy? There is a matter we need to discuss.”<br>
<br>
Tyle turned confused eyes to Yeorlorn who offered him an unreadable look before answering. “Yes, of course, Dalmariv. Please, come this way,” he said as he motioned with his hand.<br>
<br>
Tyle followed the two of them quietly, his mind a confused blur.<br>
<br>
* * *<br>
<br>
Dalmariv had removed his hood again, and quietly sipped tea from an ornate cup. “Your son Tyle, is suffering from a rare condition that in Erudin would have been diagnosed many years ago, and celebrated.”<br>
<br>
Something about the Erudite’s pompous manner grated against Tyle’s senses. There was an arrogant assured manner about the Wizard that suggested he thought he was better than any mere High Elf. Tyle didn’t doubt that Dalmariv would agree with the suggestion if asked. Erudites had a way of turning self-assuredness into arrogance that was unmatched in all of Norrath. His attitude put Tyle in a defensive mood almost immediately.<br>
<br>
“Really?” Tyle said in his uniquely hoarse way. “And what kind of condition is it that nearly kills my son, but would be prized in your lands?”<br>
<br>
Yeolorn placed a hand on Tyle’s wrist, reminding the High Elf that this Erudite had just saved Mayt’s life. The only indication Dalmariv gave that he had detected the resentment in Tyle’s voice was a slight raise of his eyebrow.<br>
<br>
“The kind of condition that shows clearly that a child has been blessed with great magical powers,” he said smoothly. He placed the cup down on the small table in between the three of them and leaned forward. <br>
<br>
“Tyle, your son – Mayt is it?”<br>
<br>
Tyle nodded, his face fixed in a serious frown.<br>
<br>
“Your son, Mayt, is suffering as he is because he has great power within him.” He paused and held up a thin ebon finger. “Great powers of elemental destruction!” he said as if the ability was the greatest any living creature could possess. He looked between the two Elves, sensing their lack of comprehension. “Mayt will one day be a powerful Wizard, and when he learns to control his powers, then –“<br>
<br>
“Wizard?” Tyle interrupted. “My son has studied for years as a Cleric of Tunare! He is not a Wizard! He comes from a long line of Clerics. His mother was a Cleric, and his grandmother was a Cleric.” Tyle looked at Yeolorn, seeking support from the old Cleric. “Once we have this problem solved and he can use his magical abilities properly, he will be a Cleric. Not a Wizard.” Tyle’s voice had risen to a shrill grating tremolo. As he held an accusing finger out at the Erudite it shook slightly. “You cannot come into Felwithe, walk into the sanctity of this great house of healing, and tell ME that my son will be some agent of elemental destruction! It’s not going to happen!”  Tyle had half-risen out of his seat, and Yeolorn was tugging at his arm in an attempt to calm him.<br>
<br>
“Tyle please,” Yeolorn said, half rising himself. “You must remember that Dalmariv has just relieved your son from a great deal of pain. He might have even saved his life. You owe him a chance to speak, Tyle.”<br>
<br>
Tyle looked at the old Elf and fought to calm himself. He turned his head to Dalmariv and felt his anger spark again. The Erudite was completely nonplussed, and sat calmly, utterly unmoved by Tyle’s outburst. He scowled at the Wizard and sat down slowly.<br>
<br>
“Tyle, I mean no disrespect,” Dalmariv began, his voice soothingly calm. “You must understand that I have spent my life in the pursuit of this type of power and it’s control. For me to see someone as young as your son with so much potential is an exciting event.” He licked his lips and looked at Yeolorn before returning his gaze to Tyle and proceeding. “The problem is, Tyle, that Mayt will continually suffer from these attacks until he is trained to focus his energy properly. Children who have been blessed with this kind of power but went untrained have often died from it. I know that may seem harsh, but I speak the truth.” He turned to Yeolorn. “Master Yeolorn: were you involved in Mayt’s training as a Cleric?”<br>
<br>
“Yes, I was Dalmariv.”<br>
<br>
“And when you were training him, was he unable to learn your healing arts?”<br>
<br>
Yeolorn shook his head slowly. “No, he was not.”<br>
<br>
“Not even the simplest of your spells? No minor curative alterations? No skin-strengthening abjurations?”<br>
<br>
“No,” Yeolorn replied sadly. “We could teach him nothing.”<br>
<br>
“But surely you did detect the power within him?”<br>
<br>
“Yes, we did. It was most frustrating. He had the power, but not the ability.”<br>
<br>
“That is correct, Master Yeolorn,” Dalmariv said with some satisfaction. “And, should he ever have that ability, it will be extraordinarily weak when compared to the abilities he will – the abilities he could have if he could be trained as a Wizard. But most importantly, if he is not trained properly then he will almost surely be killed by the power within him.”<br>
<br>
Tyle’s head was spinning. If what this arrogant Erudite was saying was true, then Mayt had to become a Wizard if he was to live – that he would never be a Cleric. He stood up abruptly and turned away from the other two men to look out a window. Outside the drizzle had ended and the sun was breaking through the clouds. He folded his arms and sighed heavily. Somewhere, deep inside, he realized that it was only his desire to remember his wife that drove him to make Mayt into a Cleric – an action that was not only extraordinarily difficult for his son, but one that might also kill him. He ran a hand through his hair and down the back of his neck and sighed again. Slowly he turned to face the others.<br>
<br>
“Alright, Dalmariv,” said sadly. “When does Mayt start to learn to be a Wizard?”<br>
<br>
Dalmariv turned his dark eyes up to the old Bard and said quietly, “He already has.”<br>
