The darkness peeled away and Mayt gasped and gulped at the air as the world erupted into existence around him. His first sense was that of overwhelming pain in his head. He went to place his hand on his forehead, but after a few inches, his hand was held fast. Dimly he remembered that he knew this. He grimaced at the pain stabbing through his head brought on by his small movement. He struggled to breath deeply, to remain conscious. <br>
<br>
Slowly his memories rebuilt themselves. Down into his brain filtered the images of him lying on his back, chained down. He breathed deeply through his nose and remembered the thick dampness of his surroundings. He must be underground, he thought; it smelled like old wet stone. He felt a wave of nausea threaten to overwhelm him, and he closed his eyes to shut out the light. He fought down the lump in his throat, willing himself to calm down. He dreaded returning to the darkness of unconsciousness - the emptiness of nothing. Breathe, he told himself. Just breathe!<br>
<br>
He lay there, thinking only of his breathing, for many minutes until the nausea passed. When he felt assured enough, he opened his eyes again. Blurry grayness filled his vision. The room was dark, but not completely so. Now he remembered opening his eyes before. And – there was something else – something important about the room. He grasped futilely at his memories, trying to pluck the pertinent ones from the sea they floated in. Nothing. He couldn’t remember what it was. He opened his eyes again and allowed them to focus. Slowly the gray blobs coalesced into solid shapes, and he could make out a large globe hanging from what appeared to be a stone ceiling, confirming his belief he was in a stony subterranean room. He turned his head to his left and again waited for his eyes to focus. When they did, he saw some sort of large structure, about stomach height, possibly a workbench. It was about 10 feet away, and seemed to be cluttered with many objects. As slowly as possible, to avoid a return of nausea, he moved his head to the right. His eyes focused more quickly this time, and he soon could see the outline of another workbench, but this one was much closer. There was some sort of bulky object on the bench – maybe a sack, or blanket, or –<br>
<br>
His heart raced as fear and panic gripped him. Maella! That’s what he couldn’t remember! Maella was here! She was lying a few feet from him, on a similar structure to what he was lying on. It wasn’t a workbench, it was a table. With chains. A table with chains. He swallowed dryly and closed his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Maella?” he said weakly, his voice a dry whisper. “Maella dear? Are you alright?”<br>
<br>
“Do not trouble yourself, my friend. She is fast asleep. Perhaps it is best to allow her to rest.”<br>
<br>
The voice seemed to bellow in the darkness, echoing off the walls, and Mayt realized how quiet he had been speaking. The sound brought a new wave of pain with it, and he groaned slightly.<br>
<br>
“You were so quiet,” the voice said smoothly. “I didn’t wish to wake you.” <br>
<br>
The kind words didn’t match the ominous dread Mayt was filled with when he spoke.<br>
<br>
“Close your eyes, my good friend and I will light the room. I don’t wish you to be hurt unnecessarily.”<br>
<br>
Mayt closed his eyes tightly and felt the hot sting of bright light from beyond his eyelids. He jerked his head to the side to avoid the white knife of light slamming into his head.<br>
<br>
“Take your time, my friend, we have all the time in the world, you and I.” Again the voice was smooth and calm.<br>
<br>
Mayt kept his eyes shut and thought urgently. Even through his disorientation he knew the situation was poor, but as a Wizard, he had resources. All he had to do was find a way to cast an evacuation spell and he could whisk Maella and himself away to Faydark. Casting the spell would be difficult lying on his back and chained down, but not impossible. The problem was, an evacuation spell took a long time to cast and he was sure his ‘friend’ knew that, and planned to interrupt whatever spell Mayt would cast. Quickly, he developed a plan. When he opened his eyes, he would determine how many people there were in the room with him. If it was just the one owner of the voice, then he would wait until the person was far enough away from him that he couldn’t reach him. Then he would cast a quick rooting spell, something he was sure he could do in the shackles, and root his captor away from him. Once he was rooted, Mayt would cast the evacuation spell without risk of being interrupted. Even if it took him a few tries, he would have the time to complete the spell in safety. He also figured, though, that this person knew him well enough, that he might be expecting him to do such a thing. He would have to bide his time carefully, and wait until the perfect moment arrived. He calmed himself, forcing his mind to slow down, as he always did during combat. He was pretty sure he had the strength to cast the evacuation spell, and the root spell was so simple it barely took any noticeable energy to cast.<br>
<br>
With his plan settled, he slowly parted his eyelids and allowed the light to stream in. His eyes slammed shut instantly, and then fluttered as he blinked away the light. Slowly, a bit at a time, he worked them half open and looked around the room slowly. There was a large glowing ball of light directly above him and he could sense at least two others on either side of him, near the ceiling. The room was indeed built out of stone, and he could see no windows anywhere, again suggesting he was correct, and the room was underground. When he moved his head to the right, toward Maella, he was surprised to see a dark faced man smiling back at him, only a few feet away. He was sitting cross-legged in a chair, his arms folded casually across his knee, and he had a disturbing smile on his face, a face that was directly in line with his own. Mayt swallowed slowly.<br>
<br>
“Well, good morning,” the Erudite said brightly. “How wonderful it is to see you awake. I apologize for the blows to the head I had to administer, but I’m sure you understand it was necessary.” He stood up slowly, his right hand resting on the back of the chair he’d been sitting in.<br>
<br>
Mayt looked past him at Maella lying on the large stone structure across from him. He thought it looked like an altar, and a shiver ran through him.<br>
<br>
The Erudite followed Mayt’s gaze and looked at Maella himself. “Ah, your lovely daughter,” he said. “Don’t worry Mayt, she was unharmed. I would hate to have such a fragile young thing hurt,” he said, his lips forming into a pout. He reached out to touch a strand of Maella’s hair that was lying beside her head on the stone slab. “You have a most beautiful daughter Mayt. You should be very proud.” He looked down at her and smiled, a few of her golden hairs caressing the palm of his hand.<br>
<br>
Mayt’s stomach filled with revulsion and he struggled to remain calm as the Erudite touched Maella’s hair but the desire to strike at his captor with all the energy he possessed burned through him. He barely restrained himself, but through his anger he realized that he needed to reserve his strength for later and reminded himself that his primary responsibility was to get Maella to safety. Revenge could come later. He also knew that chances were he wouldn’t get an offensive spell off before the man interrupted his casting, and then any possibility of surprise would be lost. No, he thought, I must wait my time.<br>
<br>
The Erudite looked up from Maella and tilted his head slightly. “Oh, but you must forgive me,” he said. “I have completely forgotten my manners.”  He removed his hand from Maella’s hair and turned to face his captive. “Mayt, allow me to introduce myself. My name is Thulinkar,” he said and bowed formally. “And I, Mayt, am one of your greatest admirers.” He smiled, as if that was somehow comforting.<br>
<br>
“You have a very strange way of showing it Thulinkar,” Mayt replied hoarsely. “I do not recall having any great admirers before, but I would not have expected them to abduct me and my daughter and chain us down to two stone slabs below the ground in some damp dungeon.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar frowned sadly. “Oh my dear Mayt, I’m only doing this for your own protection. If I allowed you to walk around freely, I would have to subdue you repeatedly, and I don’t wish to hurt you.” He turned and began to walk away from Mayt, past his feet. “In fact, Mayt, I really do treasure you. You’re going to allow me to achieve something I’ve worked very, very hard at for many, many years.”<br>
<br>
Mayt followed him with his eyes until he stopped at another, much smaller, stone altar. Mayt guessed he was over ten feet away from him. This was his chance! He cleared his mind instantly and focused a tiny bit of magical power into a spell of rooting and cast it on Thulinkar. As the magic flowed from his body, he felt something odd, as if the power of the spell was being absorbed before it could manifest itself. At the same time, he realized Thulinkar wasn’t moving, and seemed completely unconcerned. He had expected him to at least try to make it to where he was laying, but instead the Erudite just smiled back at Mayt and appeared to watch. And wait.<br>
<br>
Maella shrieked. <br>
<br>
Mayt’s head whipped around to face his daughter and see her body convulsing as her cry was strangled in her throat. His eyes grew wide in astonishment and then flashed to Thulinkar. There were no telltale strands of green energy twisting around the Erudite as Mayt would have expected to see. Instead, there was nothing.<br>
<br>
“Would you like some tea Mayt?” Thulinkar said calmly.<br>
<br>
“What happened?” Mayt croaked desperately. He returned his eyes to Maella, whose body had stopped convulsing. She was once again asleep, or at least unconscious.<br>
<br>
“No tea then?” he asked. “Very well. Perhaps later.”<br>
<br>
“What happened? What have you done to me? What have you done to my daughter?” Mayt asked, his weak voice thick with fear.<br>
<br>
“Well, you certainly can’t expect me to just allow you to cast spells whenever you wish, do you? I went through the trouble of getting you here didn’t I? You have to expect me to want to keep you here for at least a little while, my friend.” He walked over to Mayt carrying a small cup on a small plate. He stopped beside Mayt, raised the small cup to his lips and sipped delicately. As he placed the cup back on its plate, he smiled slightly and said  “Just relax, my friend, and I’ll explain how you’re going to help me with a little experiment.”<br>
