“Have you ever heard of Miragul? Thulinkar asked with a smile.<br>
<br>
“Miragul?” Mayt questioned. His mind was a blur of confusion. Somehow his power had affected Maella – had hurt Maella. He shook his head as if doing so would clear it and allow him to think properly.<br>
<br>
“Yes, my friend. Miragul. Surely you have heard of him?”<br>
<br>
Time! Mayt thought. I must keep him talking long enough for me to figure out what is happening to me. “Yes I have heard of Miragul,” he said weakly. “He was a necromancer of great power.” He paused, to emphasize the point. “He worked around Erudin for a long time, and was instrumental in creating the city of Paineel.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar smiled deeply. “Yes Mayt! Very good! Your grasp of history is excellent. Miragul was indeed a powerful Necromancer, and he had a part in the creation of Paineel. There is much you do not know, though.” He paused and seemed to consider Mayt carefully. “Have you ever been to Paineel Mayt?”<br>
<br>
“No,” Mayt replied. “They would despise me there, and kill me on sight, I am sure.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar’s smile deepened. “There! You see? That is just one reason why I must keep you under careful watch. If I don’t you’ll be off and away from me, and since we are now in the very heart of Paineel, you would be killed quickly if you even set a foot outside the security of these walls.” He swept his hand casually around the room and moved closer to Mayt. “As I said before, my friend, I treasure you, and I wish to keep you safe from harm.” He reached out and touched Mayt’s cheek lightly. “I have such great plans for you…” he said softly, his voice trailing off.<br>
<br>
Mayt flinched at his touch, revulsion mixing with fear and forming a ball in the pit of his stomach. He tried to speak clearly. “Thulinkar,” he began. “I harbor no hatred for anyone, even if they wish to kill me. I am a member of the great guild Evoluxa, and I was, for a time, an officer of that guild. We seek to bring the races together – to find strength in our commonalities. If you need something from me, I am sure we can work out a compromise. I am positive we can fulfill your goal without the need of violence. If you do not trust me, then keep me around until your goals have been met. All you need do is release my daughter, and I will be your willing servant. You have my word.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar looked away from Mayt and sighed deeply. “Oh my friend, I know much of the great Evoluxa, and I’m continually amazed at how effectively Lokus has managed to gather together such a disparate group of individuals. It truly impresses me to no end.” He looked down at Mayt again and touched his forehead with his hand, gently stroking his fingers through the Elf’s hair. Again Mayt found himself growing nauseous at his touch. “Unfortunately, my dear Mayt, what I want, you would never willingly give, regardless of your much-touted Evoluxan ideals.” He paused and looked deeply into Mayt’s eyes. “No,” he whispered, “no, you would not give what I seek.”<br>
<br>
Mayt started to speak again but Thulinkar put a finger to his lips, silencing him. “Perhaps you should hear more of Miragul, my friend.” He turned slowly and placed his hands behind his back as he walked across the room leisurely, speaking calmly as he did. “Miragul was not a Necromancer initially, Mayt. He was a practitioner of the lighter arts and had careers as a Wizard, Enchanter and Magician early in his long and famous life. He was one of those unique individuals who constantly seeks out knowledge.” He paused, twenty paces away, and turned to look back at Mayt. “Soon he had mastered all the common schools of magic, but like any great mind, he yearned for more knowledge. And, as a seeker of knowledge, his greatest enemy was time. He didn’t have enough time to learn all he wished to learn. Over the years he had developed an immense collection of magical items – artifacts of all kinds, some of enormous power. He soon realized time was his most relentless enemy and he would never have the chance to study all he had found.” Thulinkar was staring into the distance across the room. He seemed rapt with his own story, his voice rising and falling with passion as he spoke. “And so, in an effort to steal time and cheat death, he threw his powerful mind to the task of learning the dark arts of Necromancy. He believed that within that school of magic he’d find enough secrets of life and death that he would find a way to eliminate his last great foe: death itself.”<br>
<br>
“I still don’t see what all this had to do with me or Maella Thulinkar,” Mayt said. “Again, I repeat that I would be more than willing to help you with any problems you have. We can come to an arrangement, and you have my word I will help you in any way I can. All you have to do is let my daughter go.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar chuckled quietly. Mayt thought he noise was wholly evil and it sent another shiver along his spine.<br>
<br>
“My friend, you would be well advised to refrain from offering help when you do not know what form that help might take.” He chuckled again and held out his hand, palm toward Mayt. “But please, lend me some more of your patience, and soon you will understand why I cannot ask you for your help and how you will soon be helping me more than you could guess.” He looked down at the floor, as if gathering his thoughts. “As I was saying, Miragul learned the dark secrets of Necromancy. His previous knowledge and profound intellect allowed him to learn in a few short years what it would take an average man a lifetime. Soon he knew more about death than any mortal, and he returned to his sanctuary to utilize this knowledge.” He looked up at Mayt and began walking slowly toward him. “You see, Mayt, Miragul wanted to live forever.” He walked past Mayt toward the stone altar to Mayt’s left and grabbed a large book resting on top of a large pile and held it up. “This tome here contains the information regarding his experiments with life and death. You cannot imagine the difficulty I had in obtaining this great piece of work.” His eyes turned hard and distant. “I have paid more for this book than you will ever know,” he said softly. After an uncomfortable silence he blinked and looked down at Mayt. “But that is of no consequence to you or I for very soon it will not matter any more.”<br>
<br>
Mayt stared back at Thulinkar confusedly. “Ah yes, I know what you’re thinking Mayt. You still don’t see what this has to do with you. Patience. I am coming to it shortly.” He walked to Mayt holding the book in both hands, clutched to his chest. “This book contains the secret to everlasting life Mayt! Just think of it! To live forever! To never die! To be … a god!<br>
<br>
“Thulinkar,” Mayt said softly. “For every action in the universe there is another action – one that works to oppose the first, or to negate it. There cannot be life without death. These things must be in balance.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar nodded, pursed his lips and raised his eyebrows, obviously impressed with Mayt’s comment. “You are absolutely correct Mayt! Your wisdom is greater than I would have expected. Once again, I am most fortunate to have met you, even though the condition of our meeting is not conducive to the formation of a friendship,” he smiled.<br>
<br>
“Besides that,” Mayt continued, “as far as I can recall, Miragul failed in his attempt to live forever. He lives now as a mindless zombie – a creature of undeath.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar nodded again, this time more firmly. “Yes, yes, Mayt. Again you’re correct. Miragul failed. The process destroyed his very soul, and now he walks Norrath as a mere shadow of his former self. His essence, his essential being, was destroyed when he preformed the ritual to grant himself eternal life.” He held up the large book with one hand. “His experiments are detailed here quite well, and thus his mistake is apparent.” He turned around and placed the book back on the stone workbench. “But with his failure the path to success was made clear.” He steepled his index fingers and placed them to his lips. “You see, Miragul found out that a person’s soul has limited power. The Necromancers have long used this fact to manipulate a person’s life as a toy. Miragul figured out how to separate the soul from the body and mastered the skills of creating and manipulating the body. He used those skills to make for himself a new body and then proceeded to transfer his soul into the newly made vessel. His body now lives, and will continue to live forever, but his soul was not transferred and thus he walks the lands as a mindless undead creature.” Thulinkar began pacing slowly away past Mayt. “For many years it was thought that Miragul’s soul had been trapped in a special container and that he had merely made a miscalculation in his experiment, trapping his soul in the container.” He turned back to Mayt, a sly grin on his face. “I have discovered what thousands of other Necromantic scholars have failed to discover. I have solved an ages-old puzzle that no one else has managed to solve.” He turned and pressed a finger into his chest. “I know,” he said, his voice rising, “what really happened.” His face was fixed in a self-satisfied grin. “Miragul’s soul was not trapped in any vessel as so many scholars have thought. It was destroyed in the process. Miragul had not made a mistake in his experiment. He simply did not understand what you have so recently proven you understand. He did not realize that there would be a cost for transferring a soul. He didn’t know of the balance that must exist with the universe. As you so eloquently pointed out, Mayt, you can achieve nothing without something in exchange.” His voice was rising as if he had just won a great victory. “Here is what I know that Miragul did not know: the price to transfer a soul from one vessel to another is the destruction of a soul!” He looked at Mayt triumphantly.<br>
<br>
Mayt spoke calmly. If he could convince Thulinkar that his goals were unobtainable then maybe he could save Maella and himself. “Yes Thulinkar, that is exactly what I said earlier. You cannot get something for nothing. This is why your plan will fail. I can do nothing to help you and if you attempt this procedure you will pay with your soul.” He leaned up, straining against the chains on his wrists. “Please Thulinkar, maybe we can find another solution to your problem. If you have some disease that will claim your life soon perhaps you can be healed. Let me help you.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar shook his head sadly. “So close, and yet so far, Mayt. You still do not fully understand.” He made a small gesture with his left hand. “Here, I want you to meet someone.” <br>
<br>
Mayt followed his gaze to a dark corner of the room. A moment later he could see movement from within the shadows and a figure emerged from the darkness and walked toward the Erudite. As it neared him Mayt realized it was Thulinkar’s twin – a perfect copy of his flesh. The body looked past Mayt with dark soulless eyes, staring at nothing. It wasn’t a typical undead creature; its skin was unblemished and whole and it smelled clean and fresh, lacking the usual rotting flesh smell of the undead. Other than its eyes, Mayt would never suspect it was a dead thing.<br>
<br>
“Mayt, meet Thulinkar,” He said proudly. “This is possibly the greatest achievement of my life – a perfect copy of myself. A copy that will live forever. All it needs is my soul to be truly complete.”<br>
<br>
Mayt turned away from the undead thing a few feet from him and looked to Thulinkar. “Thulinkar, regardless of how long this thing will live, you will never live inside it. You said as much yourself. You cannot transfer your soul to it without destroying it in the process.” Thulinkar just smiled back. Mayt licked his dry lips and continued. “This is madness Thulinkar. Even you admit that performing this experiment will destroy your soul! You cannot win in this. Please, whatever it is you need, I am sure we can get it some other way! Do not destroy yourself this way.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar looked down and sighed, a smile remaining firmly on his face. He shook his head slowly and said, “Mayt, Mayt, Mayt. Still you don’t see. You’re so close to grasping the truth, but you still can’t see it. I never said that transferring my soul to another body would require the destruction of my soul. I said it would require the destruction of a soul! I do not intend to end my life so that I may live forever.”<br>
<br>
Mayt’s mouth hung open and his eyes stared back at Thulinkar widely. He wants to destroy my soul! He thought numbly. As he stared at Thulinkar his mind assembled the day’s information. It flirted with the concept of having his soul destroyed – the possibility of ceasing to exist. No more life. No afterlife. The end of existence. Never to see his loved ones again. Never to be rejoined with Ianarae again. Even after she died! Never to hold her again! Never to see Maella again! Ever. Images of his wife and daughter going through life without him flashed rapidly behind his eyes. Never. The possibility was so overwhelming that his mind nearly shut down with the enormity of it and he could barely reason. Thulinkar was speaking again, but he was only barely conscious of it. His mind was completely absorbed with the possibility of the end of his existence. Again he was aware of Thulinkar speaking and again he didn’t hear him. He wrestled for control of his mind, battling the fierce emotions flooding his consciousness. He tried to focus on Maella, tried to remind himself that he had to think of her safety. Perhaps if he died to save her then his life would not be in vain. Perhaps if he could assure her safety then oblivion would be an adequate exchange.<br>
<br>
Mayt knew a bit about the destruction of souls. He knew, for example, that a person’s soul could not be destroyed easily, and that it always involved consent. As he worked these barely remembered facts in his head, he realized that Thulinkar must have captured Maella as well so that he could use her as leverage against Mayt. Could he destroy his own soul just to save his daughter’s life? Shame filled him as he weighed the choice in his mind: a life for a soul. She would die, but at least her soul would live forever, and one day he’d be rejoined with her. Could he live with that? Could he live with the fact that he didn’t sacrifice himself to save his daughter? He won’t stop at anything to get what he wants, Mayt thought. Killing Maella was one thing, but torture was another altogether. How much could he allow Thulinkar to hurt Maella before he would willingly destroy his own soul? It troubled him when Maella hurt a knee, or fell while running. How much could he take?<br>
<br>
He felt Thulinkar’s hand on his face, disrupting his thoughts.<br>
<br>
“Mayt? I think I’ve lost you.” He was smiling again. “I trust the full weight of your situation has fallen upon you finally?”<br>
<br>
Mayt stared back at Thulinkar resolutely. The best course of action would be for him to look as confident as possible he thought. Maybe then he could convince Thulinkar that his idea would never work. “Thulinkar,” he began, his voice trembling, “no matter what you do to Maella I will never choose to destroy my soul for you.” He paused and calmed himself so he would sound more convincing. “No matter what you do to her,” he said with finality.<br>
<br>
Thulinkar looked back at Mayt with a puzzled look. “No matter what I do to Maella? Whatever do you mean, my friend? I could never harm such a beautiful, innocent child! Why in the world would you think I would?”<br>
<br>
It was Mayt’s turn to look puzzled. “I thought … well, I presumed that you would attempt to torture Maella so that I would willingly destroy my own soul,” he said hesitantly.<br>
<br>
Thulinkar shook his head and laughed darkly. “No, Mayt, I have no intention of getting you to destroy your own soul. I doubt I could do that, no matter what I did to your dear Maella.”<br>
<br>
Mayt furrowed his brow in confusion. “Well then, why do you have her here? From what I know a soul can only be destroyed willingly, and even though I have no understanding of the process, I thought you would teach me and then use Maella as leverage to force me to do so.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar smiled down at Mayt and placed a hand on his forehead, touching it lightly. “Ahh… there is the source of your confusion, my dear friend. A soul can, in fact, be destroyed by another person, but only in the rarest of occasions. In fact, I had never heard of such a thing until very recently.”<br>
<br>
In spite of himself, Mayt found anger flickering inside him. “Well then, if you are going to destroy my soul, then get on with it and let my daughter go.” He strained and lifted himself closer to Thulinkar. “I am getting tired of these games.” The chains clanked against the stone as he struggled closer to Thulinkar. “Go ahead and destroy my soul. And then you better run! You better run as fast as you possibly can, because if you think my death will not be avenged you are a fool of epic proportions!” Mayt snarled behind clenched teeth, “And if you want to have even the tiniest shred of compassion from those who will track you down and kill you like a dog, then you damn well better make sure my daughter remains safe!” His voice had risen to a loud growl.<br>
<br>
Thulinkar blinked in surprise. “My, my! I never would have expected such fire from someone so quiet and calm. Where is your famous understanding? Where is your famous acceptance?”<br>
<br>
“You are beyond understanding and acceptance. Now let us get on with it. I have had enough of you and this room.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar looked mildly irritated. He pressed a hand on Mayt’s chest and forced him down to the slab easily and bent close to his face. “I think you need to remember what position you’re in at this moment, and who is in charge. We can do this easily, and with as little pain as possible, or you can extend this out more than necessary.” <br>
<br>
He waved his hand and his undead clone moved away and sat down in a chair at the foot of the altar Maella was chained to. His eyes flashed at Mayt and a dark scowl spread across his face. All pretense of friendliness in his voice had evaporated.<br>
<br>
“Now, let’s get something completely clear, you stupid piece of Koada’Dal offal! You do not dictate anything here! I am the one in control, not you! I will do as I wish with you and your daughter whenever I wish, and there is nothing you can do to change that.” He extended a hand toward Maella. “I can suck the life out of your precious daughter in an instant,” he sneered. “You have no idea of the kinds and forms of torture I know. Do not press me to demonstrate them on you and your daughter.” He stepped back to Maella, keeping his eyes on Mayt, and grabbed her hair in his left fist, lifting her head slightly from the table. “I have thus far been pleasant. Do I need to demonstrate what happens when I’m unpleasant?” He waited for Mayt to respond, and after a few seconds he spat, “DO I?”.<br>
<br>
Mayt stared impotently at his daughter’s head raised a few inches above the stone altar. “No,” Mayt said weakly. “No you do not. I am sorry. Please leave her alone.”<br>
<br>
Thulinkar thrust Maella’s head down to the stone with a dull thump, eliciting a groan from her. “Do not press me further!” he growled as he stepped toward Mayt again and pointed a finger at him accusingly. “Since you still don’t seem to grasp the full scope of the situation, allow me to explain it fully. First, I do not plan on getting you to destroy your own soul. Only a complete fool would sacrifice eternity to save another’s mortal life. No. As I said before, there are ways for someone to destroy another’s soul, although it is rare.” He poked his finger at Mayt’s chest again. “You’re so ignorant you don’t even know what the prophets have written about you. Let me enlighten you.” He stomped to the workbench and retrieved another, smaller book. He opened it and began to read from it:<br>
<br>
There will be one born unto a Koada'Dal songweaver and within him the blood of Tunare's faithful will mingle with the blood of Tunare's children. <br>
<br>
Though healing his birthright be, destruction will be in his touch and Death twice shall he bring.<br>
<br>
Through his powers shall his firstborn be joined with the mother. On this day death will become life forever.<br>
<br>
He snapped the book closed and irreverently tossed it back onto the workbench. “Guess who that prophecy refers to?” he asked. Mayt just stared back in bewilderment. “Yes, Mayt, it refers to you. You’re the son of a Koada’Dal bard. You’re the offspring of a Koada’Dal and a Feir’Dal. You’re the one who tried to be a Cleric but failed, only to become a Wizard. You’re the one who will send your firstborn to Tunare, and when you do, I’m going to live forever!”<br>
<br>
Mayt’s head was spinning. “But …”<br>
<br>
“Shut up!” Thulinkar growled and pointed his finger at Mayt again. “Here’s the way it works, fool. In order to transfer a soul from one vessel to another, you need the power of another soul. I have no intention of destroying my own soul and that’s where you come in. You’re going to supply me with your daughter’s soul.”<br>
<br>
Mayt started to speak: “I will never …” <br>
<br>
Thulinkar interrupted him with a vicious slap across his face. “I told you to shut up!” he roared. “Don’t start telling me what you will and won’t do.” His hands were shaking with rage as he spoke and Mayt saw for the first time the very real flicker of madness in his eyes. “A soul can be destroyed by two people: the owner of the soul, and someone who dearly loves the owner of the soul.” He narrowed his eyes. “You’ve already seen that when you call forth magic you hurt your precious daughter. Well guess what? When you call forth a great deal of magical energy then you’ll do much more than just hurt your daughter; you’ll rip her soul from her body! And when you do, that soul will be trapped in a soul gem. Your dear Maella is wearing one in a ring on her right hand right now.”<br>
<br>
Mayt felt as if the world was crashing down upon him, pressing down on his chest. He tried to breathe but his lungs wouldn’t accept air. He moaned senselessly as realization struggled to find perch in his tortured mind.<br>
<br>
“Finally you’re starting to understand,” he grinned wickedly. “Yes, Mayt, you will destroy your precious daughter’s soul for me. And yes, Mayt, there is nothing – absolutely nothing you can do to prevent it. Soon the pain inside you will start to build, and soon the power within you will struggle to release itself. As always you’ll be powerless to prevent its release. But this time, it won’t just hurt someone nearby. This time it will rip Maella’s soul from her body and allow me to live forever.” He laughed darkly.<br>
<br>
Mayt felt sick. His entire body was trembling and he closed his eyes. “No…” he muttered softly, “no!”<br>
<br>
“Oh yes, Mayt. Yes!” Thulinkar affirmed.<br>
<br>
The world around Mayt was fading slowly and his head was swimming in an endless sea of darkness. The last thing he could hear was Thulinkar’s black laughter and his repeated cries, “Oh yes, oh yes!”<br>
<br>
<br>
